<!-- Async WordPress.com Remote Login -->
<script id="wpcom_remote_login_js">
var wpcom_remote_login_extra_auth = '';
function wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( element_id ) {
	var dom_node = document.getElementById( element_id );
	if ( dom_node ) { dom_node.remove(); }
}
function wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_classes( class_name ) {
	var dom_nodes = document.querySelectorAll( '.' + class_name );
	for ( var i = 0; i < dom_nodes.length; i++ ) {
		dom_nodes[i].remove();
	}
}
function wpcom_remote_login_final_cleanup() {
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_classes( "wpcom_remote_login_msg" );
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_remote_login_key" );
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_remote_login_validate" );
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_remote_login_js" );
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_request_access_iframe" );
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_request_access_styles" );
}

// Watch for messages back from the remote login
window.addEventListener( "message", function( e ) {
	if ( e.origin === "https://r-login.wordpress.com" ) {
		var data = {};
		try {
			data = JSON.parse( e.data );
		} catch( e ) {
			wpcom_remote_login_final_cleanup();
			return;
		}

		if ( data.msg === 'LOGIN' ) {
			// Clean up the login check iframe
			wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_remote_login_key" );

			var id_regex = new RegExp( /^[0-9]+$/ );
			var token_regex = new RegExp( /^.*|.*|.*$/ );
			if (
				token_regex.test( data.token )
				&& id_regex.test( data.wpcomid )
			) {
				// We have everything we need to ask for a login
				var script = document.createElement( "script" );
				script.setAttribute( "id", "wpcom_remote_login_validate" );
				script.src = '/remote-login.php?wpcom_remote_login=validate'
					+ '&wpcomid=' + data.wpcomid
					+ '&token=' + encodeURIComponent( data.token )
					+ '&host=' + window.location.protocol
						+ '//' + window.location.hostname;
				document.body.appendChild( script );
			}

			return;
		}

		// Safari ITP, not logged in, so redirect
		if ( data.msg === 'LOGIN-REDIRECT' ) {
			window.location = 'https://wordpress.com/log-in?redirect_to=' + window.location.href;
			return;
		}

		// Safari ITP, storage access failed, remove the request
		if ( data.msg === 'LOGIN-REMOVE' ) {
			var css_zap = 'html { -webkit-transition: margin-top 1s; transition: margin-top 1s; } /* 9001 */ html { margin-top: 0 !important; } * html body { margin-top: 0 !important; } @media screen and ( max-width: 782px ) { html { margin-top: 0 !important; } * html body { margin-top: 0 !important; } }';
			var style_zap = document.createElement( 'style' );
			style_zap.type = 'text/css';
			style_zap.appendChild( document.createTextNode( css_zap ) );
			document.body.appendChild( style_zap );

			var e = document.getElementById( 'wpcom_request_access_iframe' );
			e.parentNode.removeChild( e );

			document.cookie = 'wordpress_com_login_access=denied; path=/; max-age=31536000';

			return;
		}

		// Safari ITP
		if ( data.msg === 'REQUEST_ACCESS' ) {
			console.log( 'request access: safari' );

			// Check ITP iframe enable/disable knob
			if ( wpcom_remote_login_extra_auth !== 'safari_itp_iframe' ) {
				return;
			}

			// If we are in a "private window" there is no ITP.
			var private_window = false;
			try {
				var opendb = window.openDatabase( null, null, null, null );
			} catch( e ) {
				private_window = true;
			}

			if ( private_window ) {
				console.log( 'private window' );
				return;
			}

			var iframe = document.createElement( 'iframe' );
			iframe.id = 'wpcom_request_access_iframe';
			iframe.setAttribute( 'scrolling', 'no' );
			iframe.setAttribute( 'sandbox', 'allow-storage-access-by-user-activation allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation' );
			iframe.src = 'https://r-login.wordpress.com/remote-login.php?wpcom_remote_login=request_access&origin=' + encodeURIComponent( data.origin ) + '&wpcomid=' + encodeURIComponent( data.wpcomid );

			var css = 'html { -webkit-transition: margin-top 1s; transition: margin-top 1s; } /* 9001 */ html { margin-top: 46px !important; } * html body { margin-top: 46px !important; } @media screen and ( max-width: 660px ) { html { margin-top: 71px !important; } * html body { margin-top: 71px !important; } #wpcom_request_access_iframe { display: block; height: 71px !important; } } #wpcom_request_access_iframe { border: 0px; height: 46px; position: fixed; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; min-width: 100%; z-index: 99999; background: #23282d; } ';

			var style = document.createElement( 'style' );
			style.type = 'text/css';
			style.id = 'wpcom_request_access_styles';
			style.appendChild( document.createTextNode( css ) );
			document.body.appendChild( style );

			document.body.appendChild( iframe );
		}

		if ( data.msg === 'DONE' ) {
			wpcom_remote_login_final_cleanup();
		}
	}
}, false );

// Inject the remote login iframe after the page has had a chance to load
// more critical resources
window.addEventListener( "DOMContentLoaded", function( e ) {
	var iframe = document.createElement( "iframe" );
	iframe.style.display = "none";
	iframe.setAttribute( "scrolling", "no" );
	iframe.setAttribute( "id", "wpcom_remote_login_key" );
	iframe.src = "https://r-login.wordpress.com/remote-login.php"
		+ "?wpcom_remote_login=key"
		+ "&origin=aHR0cHM6Ly9ibGFja2xpc3RkZWNsYXNzaWZpZWQubmV0"
		+ "&wpcomid=9473618"
		+ "&time=1603821887";
	document.body.appendChild( iframe );
}, false );
</script>

		function addLoadEvent(func) {
			var oldonload = window.onload;
			if (typeof window.onload != 'function') {
				window.onload = func;
			} else {
				window.onload = function () {
					oldonload();
					func();
				}
			}
		}

<h3 id="baltimore">üî¥ 2:1 Lord Baltimore</h3>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
 <b>üî¥ Script: 2:1 Lord Baltimore </b></p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Last updated: 8/8/2015<br />
Program air date: 9/22/2014 in the US<br />
Permalink: <a href="http://wp.me/pDKwi-1e2" rel="nofollow">http://wp.me/pDKwi-1e2</a><br />
Source: Raw Scripts from Springfield [UK]: <a href="http://bit.ly/1Do56Zu" rel="nofollow">http://bit.ly/1Do56Zu</a><br />
<b>NBC Episode Plot Summary:</b> <a href="http://bit.ly/1ImyyUA" rel="nofollow">http://bit.ly/1ImyyUA</a> </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<b>Created by:</b> Jon <b>Bokenkamp</b><br />
<b>Director:</b> Michael W <b>Watkins</b><br />
<b>Writers:</b> Jon <b>Bokenkamp</b>, John <b>Eisendrath</b></p>
<p>&nbsp; </p>
<h3>Script: 2:1 Lord Baltimore</h3>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<i><b>Blurb</b>  Red starts out in Cameroon trying to get the name of the bounty hunter Berlin has hired to find him. It is Lord Baltimore, a notorious cyber-sleuth.</i></p>
<blockquote><p>
[‚ô´ music ZZ Top&#8217;s &#8220;La Grange&#8221; plays  ]<br />
Man: Whoo!<br />
[ Indistinct shouting  ]<br />
<i>‚ô´ Haw, haw, haw, haw Well, I hear it&#8217;s fine ‚Äì<br />
If you&#8217;ve got the time ‚Äì Ha! ‚Äì<br />
And the 10 to get yourself in ‚Äì </i><br />
[ Gunfire, shouting  ]<br />
<i>A-hmm, hmm<br />
And I hear it&#8217;s tight &#8216;Most every night<br />
Man: Yeah! But now I might be mistaken<br />
A-hmm, hmm, hmm [ Guitar solo  ] </i>
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ Cheering  ] [ Indistinct conversations ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ Chuckling  ] Oh, my stars. Is that how you cope with this insufferable humidity? I couldn&#8217;t do it.<br />
Yaabari: We had an agreement.<br />
<b>Red:</b> We did.<br />
Yaabari: I told you if I ever found you in my territory again, I&#8217;d kill you.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Tell the boy not to pull on the brim of the hat.<br />
Yaabari: What&#8217;s in the box?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;ve come to propose a business transaction.<br />
Yaabari: No, we have no business. The box.<br />
[ Men shouting in Bantu  ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Typically, I steer clear of tin-pot dictators who employ boy soldiers, but I&#8217;m afraid this situation is unique.<br />
[ Speaking Bantu  ] [ Man holds gun to Red&#8217;s head ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Well, now you&#8217;re being shortsighted.<br />
[ Speaking Bantu  ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Tell him to put the gun down.<br />
[ Shouting in Bantu  ] [ Yaabari shoots man  ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m glad to know you&#8217;re a man of decisive action. You see, Yaabari, you didn&#8217;t actually find me. I found you. And while your prepubescent ruffians may not know it, they brought me here to strike a deal that could benefit all of us.<br />
Yaabari: What kind of deal?<br />
<b>Red:</b> A man calling himself Berlin hired a bounty hunter to find me and my associates. That bounty hunter worked for you. <h3>Script: 2:2 Monarch Douglas Bank</h3>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><i><b>Blurb:</b> Monarch Douglas Bank, the preferred bank of the criminal elite, has been robbed ‚Äì but no money was taken. Red&#8217;s ex-wife, Naomi Hyland, has been captured by Berlin who promises to send her back &#8220;piece by piece.&#8221; </i></p>

<h3>Script: 2:3 Dr James Covington</h3>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<i><b>Blurb:</b> Illegal organ transplantation is keeping children ‚Äì and criminals ‚Äì alive. Red faces disloyalty in his ranks. Samar Navabi joins the Task Force. Liz has a dream. Red and Naomi Hyland reconnect after 20 years. </i></p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[Indistinct conversations] [Laughter]<br />
Man: You had to know we would find you.<br />
Paul Wyatt: I didn&#8217;t run.<br />
Man: Yes.<br />
Wyatt: I could have gone to the police.<br />
Man: And we would have gone to see your beautiful family.<br />
Wyatt: Please. There must be another way.<br />
Man: I wasn&#8217;t sent to negotiate.<br />
[ Wyatt upends table, runs off ] [ People gasp ] [ Grunts ] [ Gasps ] [ Tires screech]<br />

Driver: Calm down, man. Calm down.<br />

[ Wyatt collapses ]<br />
He&#8217;s out.</p>
<p>Woman: Pulse, blood pressure steady.<br />
Man: He&#8217;s waking up. Let&#8217;s get him into surgery.<br />
Wyatt: Please.<br />
Man: We have a drop site at southeast. Fielding is standing by for the corpse.<br />

Man. Tell him no more than 40 minutes. The doctor is scrubbing down.<br />

Man: Indeed. See for yourself. Polymer over steel, ambidextrous controls.<br />
Vargas: [ Calls over to Niko ] Be right with you.  We&#8217;ve been through this: Berlin prefers firearms manufactured in Russia or Eastern Europe. Just give me the same shipment as last time.<br />
[ To Niko ] My apologies. I expected to have that all wrapped up before you arrived. Where are we?<br />
Niko: It&#8217;s done.<br />
Vargas: Reddington bought the photo op?<br />
Niko: I didn&#8217;t even need to present real evidence his men had betrayed him. He has become reckless, unstable. It seems our arrangement is off to a promising start. Regarding that arrangement, I think we need to revisit the terms. I betrayed Raymond Reddington. He is not gonna just absorb that blow and move on. I need him taken care of.<br />
Vargas: If Berlin wanted Reddington dead, he would have done that already.‚ô§<br />
Niko: Yeah, well, things have changed. You&#8217;re doing business with me now. I know everything about Reddington&#8217;s operation, and I&#8217;m willing to hand over all of that to your employer, but I need Reddington gone. I can&#8217;t be an effective partner to Berlin if I&#8217;m always looking over my shoulder.<br />
Vargas: Set a meeting with Reddington. My people will take care of the rest.</p>
<p>Ressler: Landlord&#8217;s still not answering.<br />
Liz: This has to be the place. We&#8217;ve been to every retail store, office park, and restaurant in the area. We got 20 minutes till Covington kills his next victim. What are you doing?<br />
Ressler: I like to keep a spare key in the trunk.</p>
<p>[Grunts] [Crowbar clangs] [Cellphone beeps]<br />
Aram: Hey. Anything?<br />
Liz: A whole lot of nothing.<br />
Ressler: Hey, Keen. Look at this. We got a stairway to the lower level.<br />
Aram: Lower level?<br />
Liz: Yeah. There&#8217;s some kind of access stairway.<br />
Aram: The building plans filed with the city don&#8217;t say anything about a lower level.<br />
[TV chatter in distance] [Monitor beeping] [TV chatter] </p>
<p>Ressler: Hands. Hands. Let me see your hands.<br />
Man: You can&#8217;t be in here. Aah!<br />
Ressler: I got this.<br />
Man: [Grunts] Wait, sir. Look, don&#8217;t go in there.<br />
Ressler: Sit down.<br />
Man: Please. I&#8217;m begging you.<br />
Ressler: I said, &#8220;sit.&#8221;<br />
[ Indistinct conversation ] [ Monitor beeping ]<br />
Liz: Back away from the table.<br />
Covington: I don&#8217;t know who the hell you are ‚Äì<br />
Liz: Hands in the air! Step away from the table now!<br />
Covington: You don&#8217;t know what you&#8217;re doing.<br />
Liz: It&#8217;s over, Dr. Covington. We know about your business. You lost your license for performing an experimental operation on a child. Well, not this one. Not today.<br />
Covington: I&#8217;m not trying to hurt the boy. I&#8217;m trying to save him. His name is Daniel. If he doesn&#8217;t get these lungs in the next 24 hours, he won&#8217;t survive.<br />
Liz: He needs to be in a hospital.<br />
Covington: It&#8217;s too late for that. I&#8217;m performing this operation. If you want to stop me, you&#8217;ll have to shoot me.<br />
[Gun cocks]<br />
Ressler: Won&#8217;t be a problem.<br />
Covington: There are strict rules controlling who gets access to donor organs and when. In the present system, they offer adult donor lungs to adults, even if there are children with a more urgent need.<br />
Liz: I&#8217;m not discussing this with you.<br />
Covington: I took adult lungs and transplanted them into a little girl. That&#8217;s why I lost my license ‚Äî for saving her life.<br />
Liz: So you know better?<br />
Covington: Okay, putting adult lungs into children is a risk. But I believe, in many cases, we have an obligation to try. And I&#8217;m not the only one. Times are changing. There&#8217;s even an official appeals process for these cases now.<br />
Liz: Then his parents can request an exception to the rule.<br />
Covington: And risk being turned down. At least here, I guarantee him a chance.<br />
Liz: You killed Paul Wyatt. You ripped the heart out of his chest.<br />
Covington: Look, you can think whatever you want about me, but every dime I&#8217;ve made on criminals like Paul Wyatt has been spent to build and operate this place. All that matters today is that there will be no tomorrow for this boy if I don&#8217;t do this transplant. The donor material is already here. If we don&#8217;t use it, it will die, just like he will.</p>
<p>Liz: If we take him in now, that kid won&#8217;t make it. Can you live with that?<br />
Ressler: Covington&#8217;s not just a surgeon, Keen. He&#8217;s a killer.<br />
Liz: Yeah, and right now, he&#8217;s that boy&#8217;s only chance. Look at his parents. What if that were your kid?<br />
Ressler: And what if something goes wrong? What if he dies on the table? How do we explain that?<br />
Liz: Can you cover with Cooper and Aram? Just buy us some time.<br />
Ressler: Liz, this is way over the line.<br />
Liz: We have to let him do this.</p>
<p>[Door opens]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Niko, you&#8217;re all in a sweat. What&#8217;s so important that it couldn&#8217;t wait?<br />
Niko: We&#8217;ve been partners a long time, and we&#8217;ve had more than our share of success, so I wanted to pay you the courtesy of looking you in the eye when I tell you you&#8217;re out.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I see. And you&#8217;re speaking for&#8230;?<br />
Niko: Everybody. We&#8217;re united. You&#8217;ve become a liability.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Don&#8217;t forget who you&#8217;re talking to.<br />
Niko: How could I? Especially since it&#8217;s our last conversation. Raymond Reddington, Mr. Vargas. [Gun cocks] I may have misled you. Someone did take Berlin up on his offer, but it wasn&#8217;t Laskin and Russo. It was me.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Well played, Niko. I didn&#8217;t think you had it in you.<br />
Niko: [ To Vargas ] Kill him.<br />
[ Red calmly walks over to Mr Vargas ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> I find chrome to be a bit ostentatious. [ Takes gun from Vargas ]<br />
Vargas: I&#8217;m sorry, Mr. Demakis. The truth is I&#8217;m the one who misled you.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [Chuckles] You know, when I was 15, I had a summer job installing carpets for Albert Kodagolian on Lake Charlevoix. Horrible job, hot, indoors, forced to listen to &#8220;The Gambler&#8221; on 8-track while the rest of the world was at the beach. Three days into the job, I knew I had to quit. I asked my father for advice. All he wanted to know was whether I&#8217;d given my word to Mr. Kodagolian that I&#8217;d work the summer. I told him I had. My father suggested I stick it out. I&#8217;d given my word. Worst eight weeks of my life. Until the last day. Mr. Kodagolian shows up at the jobsite, pulls me aside, and tells me that in 27 years, no kid has ever made it through the summer, gives me a bonus $40. The most valuable money I&#8217;ve ever made. A priceless lesson about life. Value loyalty above all else.‚ô§ Oh! I buried the lead. Turns out the Indonesian government has chosen to contract our company to run the Port Of Tan Kulu. The Deputy Minister of Transportation was not a fan. Fortunately, he was also gravely ill and in desperate need of a heart transplant. He died this morning. Apparently, the arrangements he&#8217;d made to secure a donor heart didn&#8217;t pan out.‚ô§ The new deputy minister sees things our way. Lucky, I guess.<br />
Niko: I don&#8217;t believe luck had anything to do with it.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You&#8217;re right. Luck rarely has anything to do with it.‚ô§ [shoots him]<br />
Vargas: Honestly, how many times have we discussed this?<br />
<b>Red:</b> What?<br />
Vargas: You you know I don&#8217;t like being around the bloody st‚Äì  Oh. I need to be allowed to leave the room before the blood. You know I don&#8217;t have a strong constitution.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Give him his seat. He&#8217;s gonna faint. Oh, my.<br />
[Breathing shakily] [Monitor beeping] [Police radio chatter]<br />
Vargas: Thank you.</p>
<p>Liz: Hey, you think Reddington knew that Covington was trying to save kids?<br />
Ressler: For every child Covington saved, there were three killers like B.B. he kept alive to victimize innocent people.<br />
Liz: It&#8217;s a trade-off I&#8217;d make.‚ô§<br />
Ressler: [Scoffs] The fact that you&#8217;re even thinking about what trade-offs you&#8217;d make, what rules you&#8217;d ignore ‚Äì the Agent Keen I met a year ago would have never done that.</p>
<p><i>[‚ô´ Fink&#8217;s &#8220;Pilgrim&#8221; plays] </i> </p>
<p>Samar: You caught Covington, and the child is in recovery. It sounds like a victory.<br />
Liz: Yeah.<br />
Samar: You guys don&#8217;t celebrate when you close a big case? Come on. Let me buy you a drink.<br />
Liz: Thanks, but I think I&#8217;m just gonna head out.</p>
<p><i>‚ô´ Come a long way </i> </p>

<p>&nbsp; </p>
<h3>Script: 2:4 Dr Linus Creel</h3>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<i><b>Blurb:</b> Red calls Liz&#8217;s attention to a spate of unusual killings and suggests the government may still be doing mind control experiments. Liz may have a rare genetic marker. Red offers to protect Naomi and her husband Frank from Berlin.</i><br />
&nbsp; </p>
<p>[Sirens wailing] [Siren blares] [Engine revs] [Horn honks] [Gulps] [Baby crying] [Jackhammer rumbling] [Heartbeat pounding, deep breathing]<br />
Bank officer: Proceedings close Tuesday.<br />
Woman: That&#8217;s in six days.<br />
Bank officer: We submitted a delinquency letter three weeks ago. Reports had been failed.<br />
Woman: I know I&#8217;m behind, but I-I&#8217;m owed unemployment, and my sister said that she can help make the difference up.<br />
Bank officer: Yeah, I wish there was something more I could do.<br />
Woman: You can&#8217;t kick us out! [Sighs] I have a second job interview tomorrow ‚Äì<br />
Bank officer: It&#8217;s out of my hands.<br />
[ Woman leaves, but returns. She has gun, shoots loan officer. People screaming ]<br />
Dr Linus Creel: [ Outside, in car. Speaks into recorder ] Shots fired, colon, multiple, period. Final phase successful, period. Activation of ar105 complete, period. End of entry.</p>
<p>Naomi: The answer is no. I gave up one life. Do you think I&#8217;m gonna start over, do it all again?! You&#8217;re crazier than I imagined!<br />
<b>Red:</b> You can&#8217;t go back to Philadelphia. It&#8217;s too dangerous.<br />
Naomi: What do you think I&#8217;m gonna do? Stay here in in this? I can&#8217;t believe you brought me here. I&#8217;ll tell you where I&#8217;m gonna go home, with my husband. Frank has two daughters. You think he&#8217;s just gonna walk out on them?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I need to know where Jennifer is.<br />
Naomi: I kept my end of the bargain, didn&#8217;t say anything about you or Elizabeth.<br />
<b>Red:</b> How much does she know?<br />
Naomi: Very little. A- are the [Sighs] Are the two of you, what, working together? I don&#8217;t even want to know how you pulled that off.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Listen to me about Jennifer, I can protect her.<br />
Naomi: I&#8217;m never going to tell you where my daughter is. Because of you, I&#8217;m forced to finally tell Frank, a man who&#8217;s never kept a secret from me not only that I was married before, but that I was married to ‚Äî He sits me down, tells me he&#8217;s sorry for me. Try and wrap your warped mind around that. The man&#8217;s entire life is upended. All he can think about is me.<br />
<b>Red:</b> The arrangements have been made passports, identities, a new life. Talk it over with Frank. If you love him, you&#8217;ll let me help.</p>
<p>[Door opens]<br />
Liz: Where&#8217;s Naomi Hyland?<br />
<b>Red:</b> In safe hands.<br />
Liz: What does that mean ‚Äì you&#8217;ve already set her up with a cozy new life in Saint Kitts or Solvang?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Solvang? I never send anyone I care about to Solvang.<br />
Liz: She spent nine days with Berlin. We have to debrief her. She could know something his real name, his location.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Did you read about that housewife in Reston? She shot a bank manager.<br />
Liz: You&#8217;re not hiding her from the FBI. You&#8217;re hiding her from me.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Violent crime in D.C. is at a 20-year low, and yet in the last four months, there have been seven random acts of violence by individuals with no prior criminal record. Lizzy, what do you know about social psychology? It&#8217;s the study of how our behavior is influenced by the world around us. Not influenced manipulated. In what little time I devote to the judgment your government has made about my character and how I treat my fellow man, I can&#8217;t help but think about how many of their own citizens they&#8217;ve treated like lab rats in the name of science. I believe this murder in Reston is part of an underground social-psychology experiment. Conducted by our government. Strap on your tinfoil hat, Lizzy.</p>
<p>Liz: According to Reddington, three recent incidents prove the U.S.government is still conducting mind-control experiments. Terry Cho, a middle-school teacher who killed seven of his coworkers during his lunch break. Construction worker Henry Lee Bryce used a hammer and a box cutter. Killed by police. The third, Maddie Thornhill, single mom who opened fire at a bank in Reston. Reddington has alleged that these crimes weren&#8217;t random, but orchestrated by spooks the government continues to finance through their black-ops budget.<br />
Ressler: Look, to be honest, I think this is a big distraction to keep us busy while Reddington spirits away his ex.<br />
Cooper: Interview the shooters and their families. Then we&#8217;ll worry about the wife.</p>
<p>Aram: Hey.<br />
Liz: What would you say if I told you to pull Frank and Naomi Hyland&#8217;s phone records for the past five years?<br />
Aram: I&#8217;d, uh, ask if you had a warrant.<br />
Liz: Would you ask me to show it to you?<br />
Aram: Why would I do that? I trust you implicitly, Agent Keen.</p>
<p>Ressler: Special Agents Ressler and Keen, FBI, here to interview Madeline Thornhill.<br />
Nurse: I&#8217;m sorry she&#8217;s on a 48-hour hold. Suicide watch, no visitors.<br />
Liz: She&#8217;s talking to someone right now.<br />
Nurse: Her psychiatrist. I&#8217;ll pass along your contact info, if you&#8217;d like.</p>
<p>Maddie:  I really don&#8217;t know when things just started to fall apart. First, it was my job.<br />
Her former boss: [ To Liz and Ressler ] Maddie was getting a ton of bad reviews on Yelp by name. People said she was unhelpful, even rude.<br />
Maddie: [ To her psychiatrist ] I don&#8217;t know why they give so much weight to those stupid things. No one seemed dissatisfied in the office, but the things they were saying about me.<br />
Former boss: I tried to work with her on it, but she kept making excuses crazy stuff, paranoid.<br />
Liz: Like what?<br />
Former Boss: Like somebody was out to get her, posting fake reviews. She was argumentative. Finally, I just had to let her go.<br />
Maddie: [ To psychiatrist ]Then things fell apart with Charlie.<br />
Charlie (Maddie&#8217;s former boyfriend): I really had no choice. I&#8217;m in the middle of a custody battle, and the court&#8217;s got me under a microscope. It came down to her or my kids.<br />
Ressler: Did you ever see her mistreat them?<br />
Maddie: I loved his kids. I would never hurt any child. But social services started getting anonymous calls that when I was over there, they were crying or whatever. I actually thought about getting one of those spycams, you know? But then I&#8217;m thinking ‚Äì If it&#8217;s come to that, what&#8217;s the point? He just dumped me after almost two years. One minute, I&#8217;ve got a great job, a boyfriend, and the next ‚Äì<br />
Loan Officer: She started making late payments on her mortgage. We tried to help, but she was three months behind. Without any income, we had to foreclose.<br />
Maddie: They just took it. Like it was just a house.<br />
But it wasn&#8217;t just a house. Was it?<br />
Maddie: No. It was me.</p>
<p>Liz: Maddie Thornhill told us her life fell apart after a series of anonymous accusations.<br />
Samar: The shooter I spoke to said the same thing. In his case, it was accusations of pedophilia. There were no witnesses, no victims ever came forward, but the school didn&#8217;t want to take chances, so they fired him.<br />
Liz: Their problems metastasized like a cancer, striking to the heart of these victims&#8217; identities.<br />
Ressler: Victims? These aren&#8217;t the victims, Keen, these are the perps. The people they killed are the victims.<br />
Liz: All I&#8217;m saying is that some people aren&#8217;t wired to handle stress, and someone took advantage of that.</p>
<p>Aram: Agent Keen had me expedite DNA profiles. All three perpetrators possess the MAO-A 2R gene.<br />
Liz: The extreme-warrior gene.<br />
Aram: Clinical studies have proven people who possess this gene are prone to aggressive, antisocial behavior.<br />
Ressler: Are you suggesting the government has identified people with mild genetic abnormality and is turning them into killers?<br />
That&#8217;s exactly what we&#8217;re suggesting.</p>
<blockquote><p>
Female reporter: Police have not yet commented on how the chase started, but sources say the driver shot three clerks this morning inside of a convenience store.
</p></blockquote>
<p>Creel: Phase 2 concluded, period. Ar106 showing signs of deterioration, comma, accelerating to Final break.</p>
<blockquote><p>
Male reporter: Vehicle with a weapon.<br />
Oh, no.<br />
Male reporter: O-okay, officers have just opened fire.
</p></blockquote>
<p>Creel: We are going to Final phase successful, period. [Clears throat] Activation of subject ar106 concluded, period. End of entry.</p>
<p>[Beep] Woman: Senator&#8217;s office. How may I help you?<br />
Creel: Hello, yes. This is Dr. Linus Creel. I&#8217;m calling for Senator Sheridan.</p>
<p>[ Knock on door ]<br />
Cooper: The perp in the freeway shooting I hear he had this warrior gene.<br />
Liz: Yeah. Agent Navabi has identified 11 other cases in the last 18 months. No connection other than ‚Äì<br />
Cooper: They share this gene.<br />
Liz; And it&#8217;s not just some statistical anomaly. I- it&#8217;s as if they&#8217;re being triggered.<br />
Cooper: Close the door.<br />
Liz: Sir? You know something?<br />
Cooper: Every word Reddington said about this program is true. In the army, officers sit in bars, and they talk sideways &#8220;a guy who knows a guy who knows a guy.&#8221; MKUltra was just the start. There were others quietly run in military bases and universities all across the country psychopharmaceuticals, electromagnetic pulses, microwaves that broadcast words and phrases into the brain. I love this country, but every once in awhile, you hear about something like this, some bone-evil crap that&#8217;s almost inconceivable. That&#8217;s what I hate most about this detail ‚Äì Reddington pulling up the carpet and shoving your nose deep into the filth. After a while, it&#8217;s all you can see.‚ô§ [ Pause ] Subproject 7.I<br />
Liz: Don&#8217;t know what that is.<br />
Cooper: It&#8217;s a black-budget program. It&#8217;s funded out of the D.I.A. The goal was to use genetic predispositions to train and trigger assets.<br />
Liz: If it&#8217;s black-budget, how am I supposed to gain access? </p>
<p>Senator Sheraton: I am a dear friend of Harold Cooper. He was a pallbearer in my daddy&#8217;s funeral. But I told him when he called only yahoos are interested in Subproject 7.<br />
Ressler: So you&#8217;re saying it doesn&#8217;t exist?<br />
Sheraton: You&#8217;re asking about mind control. This government can&#8217;t make up its own mind, let alone control one.<br />
Liz: Senator, is that a yes or a no?<br />

<h3>Script 2:5 The Front</h3>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<i><b>Blurb:</b> Virology, art history and environmentalism converge as a radical cult revives an ancient plague to rescue the earth from humanity. Red repairs an old film projector and tracks a young woman the &#8220;help&#8221; of the DMV.</i><br />

<b>Red:</b> Yes. The leaders of The Front.<br />
Liz: Well, how is that possible? They died trying to bomb BP&#8217;s London Office in response to the Gulf Oil Spill.<br />
<b>Red:</b> So the world believes. In truth, they took their work underground. Personally, I once admired Carrie Ann. However, since going underground, they&#8217;ve become too radical for my blood, advocates for a level of destruction that I find chilling.<br />

<b>Red:</b> I believe her husband is responsible.<br />

<b>Red:</b> Yes, but their partnership was a tenuous one. She was always the more moderate voice, only interested in operations that related directly to the environment. Beck, on the other hand, views himself as a chosen one, a messianic figure who sees humanity as a virus that needs to be eradicated in order to save the planet. I fear he got rid of his wife because she was trying to stop him from implementing a plan to do just that.</p>
<p>Liz: These are the last known photographs of Maddox Beck and his wife. They&#8217;re the founders of the Front.<br />
Aram: 2012 Firebomb strikes a Biotechpark in Boston, conducting genomics research, causing $64 million in damage. Four staff members were killed and 16 hospitalized. Ricin was mailed to the Fairbanks BLM Office, which manages Transatlantic Pipeline.<br />
Ressler: Just got off with the M.E. He&#8217;ll have a tox work-up on Beck&#8217;s wife within the hour.<br />

Ressler: Her body&#8217;s not at the morgue. She&#8217;s at City Memorial. Labor and delivery.</p>
<p>Liz: She was pregnant?<br />

<p>Aram: The soil found under the nails of Carrie Ann Beck dates back to the 14th century. It&#8217;s called Raw Sienna.<br />

<div align="left">
<p><b>Red:</b> You know, 29 years ago in Sierra Leone, there was a farmer named Samwel Zuma who had the audacity to identify several low-level Mombasa operatives to local authorities. The cartel massacred the entire family. All but the youngest son. He was sold to a local ring of flesh peddlers. The majority of children in those circumstances don&#8217;t last more than nine months. He survived eight years. He was 14 when I found him. Too old, too tall, too angry and dangerous to be of any further value.‚ô§ He was left to die, chained to a standpipe in the basement of a squalid brothel in Nairobi. Branded, burned, barely alive. So I took him. Made him well, saw to his education. He graduated university with a bachelor&#8217;s degree in English Literature. He speaks four languages fluently and can get by in a half a dozen more. He is splendid. His name is Dembe ‚Äì  Dembe Zuma.‚ô§<br />
Dembe: Raymond, don&#8217;t. That was then. It serves no purpose to kill him now.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You see that, Geoff? That is what a good man does. That is what separates men like him from men like you and me. ‚ô§<br />
[Red shoots Geoff]</p>
<p>Liz: To tell you the truth, I haven&#8217;t made a decision yet. [ Sighing ] The other day was close. I thought about telling Reddington. He&#8217;d know what to do. But the truth is, this is my responsibility ‚Äì One way or the other.<br />
Tom: I&#8217;ve answered all your questions, Liz. You can&#8217;t hide me forever.</p>

<h3 id="scimitar">üî¥ 2:7 The Scimitar</h3>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
 <b>üî¥ Script: 2:7 The Scimitar </b></p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Last updated: 8/9/2015<br />
Program air date: 11/3/2014 in the US<br />
Script with extras: <a href="http://wp.me/pDKwi-19T" rel="nofollow">http://wp.me/pDKwi-19T</a><br />

<h3>Script: 2:7 The Scimitar</h3>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<i><b>Blurb:</b> Samar killed one of Iran&#8217;s nuclear scientists and the Iranians are now out to kill one from the U.S. Liz is interrogating Tom on a rusty ship, and Berlin is about to receive a delivery which may alter his war with Red.</i></p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[Middle-Eastern music playing] [Indistinct conversations] [Music continues]<br />
[ Conversation in Farsi ‚Äì subtitles ]<br />
Kian: I believe you were staring at me.<br />
Samar: Was I?<br />
Kian: Kian.<br />
Samar: Ava. So ‚Ä¶ Were you going to keep staring or are you going to buy me a drink?<br />
Man: Cumbernauld, &#8217;55.<br />
[ Outside hotel room ]<br />
Kian: Keys. Where?<br />
Samar: Right pocket.<br />
[ End Farsi ]<br />
[Both breathing heavily] [Laughing] [Both breathing heavily] [Both laugh] </p>
<p>[ Outside. Thud, glass shatters: man dead on car top ] </p>
<p>Tom: [Screams] I&#8217;ve told you everything I know.<br />
Liz: You&#8217;ve given me pieces. You&#8217;ve helped around the margins, but I need more. I need Berlin!<br />
Tom: How much do you think I can do from in here, Liz, chained to the floor? You need to let me go, and then I can ‚Äì<br />
Liz: The arms supplier ‚Äì I want a name.<br />
Tom: I can try to reach out to Berlin, but as long as I am in here, I can&#8217;t.<br />
Liz: I want a name!<br />
Tom: [Sighs] What month is it?<br />
Liz: November.<br />
Tom: Well, happy anniversary, Liz. You go to Passionfish to celebrate? I&#8217;m gonna freeze to death down here. You know that, right? [Sighs] Sevan. Sevan Volkov. He runs arms for Berlin. He&#8217;d be able to set a meeting.<br />
Liz: That wasn&#8217;t so hard, was it? </p>
<p>Samar Navabi: So, what exactly did Reddington say?<br />
Liz: Uh, it was Dembe. He said Red had another case but he specifically asked that you come along.<br />
Samar: Does that bother you?<br />
Liz: Why would it?<br />
Samar: I thought he only spoke to you. Don&#8217;t want to step on your toes.<br />
Liz: I&#8217;m fine. My toes are fine.<br />
[ They enter record shop ]</p>
<p><b>Red:</b> [Bell dings: Record shop] Ah, ladies, thank God you showed up. I took a left turn in the Rostropovich. I&#8217;ve ended up completely lost in the Chico Hamilton. This is an addiction.<br />
I just can&#8217;t decide between ‚Äì Please pour some cold water on me, will you?<br />
Liz: Why did you want both of us here?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Both, you&#8217;re right. Thank you. Great idea. Anyway, funny story ‚Äì stop me if you&#8217;ve heard it. Persian man walks into a bar, meets a beautiful woman, has a few drinks. Next thing you know, he&#8217;s falling from a 12-story balcony.<br />
Liz: I don&#8217;t get it.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I imagine Agent Navabi does.<br />
Samar: You&#8217;re referring to Kian Nouri, the Iranian businessman who committed suicide in Dubai.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I am, except he wasn&#8217;t a mere businessman. He was one of Iran&#8217;s top nuclear scientists in Dubai to supervise purchase of several borehole gamma something-or-others. And he didn&#8217;t commit suicide. He was assassinated in a joint C.I.A./Mossad venture to undermine Iran&#8217;s nuclear program, but, then, you know this already. My understanding is, she took a little detour to Dubai for a rendezvous with Mr. Nouri so she could toss him off a building.<br />
Liz to Samar: You killed him?<br />
Samar: If you&#8217;re asking me to comment on a Mossad operation, you know I can&#8217;t do that.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I wasn&#8217;t asking. But I&#8217;m hardly one to judge. George Orwell wrote, &#8220;Those who abjure violence can do so &#8220;only because others are committing violence on their behalf. &#8221; What a visionary, but, Good Lord, his books are a downer. In any case, the bad news is, I was sharing a bowl of shisha with a Misiri minister, and they plan to retaliate. You kill their top scientist, they intend to kill yours, and they&#8217;ve dispatched a man known as &#8220;The Scimitar&#8221; to do it.<br />
Liz: The Scimitar?<br />
<b>Red:</b> This is not your average killer, Agent Keen. He&#8217;s one part hit man, two parts con man.<br />
Navabi: I&#8217;m familiar with his work.<br />
<b>Red:</b> In 2009, his target was a Sunni tribal leader named Majeed Abd Bawi. The Scimitar gained access by joining his militia. [Laughing] Oh, that&#8217;s right! Fought for the man for seven months until the day he got close enough to aerate Bawi&#8217;s carotid with a fork. He&#8217;s dedicated, resilient, cunning, responsible for the murder of dozens of high-value targets, and, according to my sources, he&#8217;s already on U.S. soil.</p>
<p>Assistant Director: Harold, I&#8217;m the Assistant Secretary of NCB. I run point on all international nuclear matters. If this guy was the threat you claim, he&#8217;d be on my radar. Who&#8217;s your source on this threat?<br />
Cooper:A confidential informant with an extremely reliable track record. I&#8217;m afraid that&#8217;s as specific as I can get. If I&#8217;m right, what&#8217;s our exposure on this?<br />
Assistant Director: Cloud Top. It&#8217;s the classified designation for a warhead project design. It&#8217;s staffed by our top three scientists. If any of them fell into the hands of a rogue nation, that country&#8217;s nuclear program would advance decades overnight.<br />
Cooper: What kind of security protocols do you have in place?<br />
Assistant Director: The DSS provides them with false identities, social security numbers, even cover professions. We hide them in plain sight, sort of a Witness Protection for high-value assets.<br />
Cooper: That&#8217;s not gonna cut it. You need to pull these people off the streets and into protective custody.<br />
Assistant Director: All right, Harold. I&#8217;ll put two of them on lock-down. I can do that without drawing too much scrutiny.<br />
Cooper: And the third?<br />
Assistant Director: That&#8217;s gonna be a problem. The D.O.D. asset is Amalia Collins Senior Engineer of our Warhead Design Team. When she&#8217;s not on active status, she serves as a professor of astrophysics at Duke.<br />
Cooper: It says here she&#8217;s scheduled to deliver a talk tonight at a symposium at the Granville Hotel.<br />
Assistant Director: D.O.D.&#8217;s reluctant to call it off at the last minute because of the scrutiny it would draw. They feel it could put her in further danger.<br />
Cooper: You mean they&#8217;re not gonna pull her?<br />
Assistant Director: There&#8217;s no indications the Iranians have any idea of her real value.<br />
Cooper: Let&#8217;s make sure it stays that way. In the meantime, we need to track this Scimitar before he&#8217;s able to I.D. our team.</p>
<p>Liz: Uh, we need to talk.<br />
Ressler: I got things under control.<br />
Liz: Uh-huh. When&#8217;s the last time you used?<br />
Ressler: Sitka, almost a week.<br />
Liz: This happens all the time ‚Äì agents taking meds to get over injuries and then they get hooked. It&#8217;s no big deal.<br />
Ressler: What are you gonna do, Keen? ‚Äì Tell Cooper I&#8217;m an addict?<br />
Liz: I want you to get help.<br />
Ressler: And I&#8217;m telling you, I can kick this on my own, and if I can&#8217;t, hell, I&#8217;ll walk into Cooper&#8217;s office myself.<br />
Liz: I got no problems with that.<br />
[ Cellphone vibrates ] </p>
<p>Liz: I got your text. What&#8217;s the problem?<br />
Samuel Aleko: Zebra mussels. Fish and game are running random inspections for invasive species.<br />
Liz: Zebra mussels. Did they go inside?<br />
Aleko: They tried to, but I held them off, but I don&#8217;t know for how long. We&#8217;re gonna either have to move the boat or him.<br />
[Lock disengages] [Door thuds]<br />
Tom: Talk to Volkov?<br />
Liz: We have a meeting this afternoon. I brought you some warmer clothes.<br />
Tom: Well, that&#8217;s nice. Now you care about me.<br />
Liz: Is that it now you&#8217;re, uh, concerned for my well-being?<br />
Tom:You can try and make yourself feel better about what you&#8217;re doing, but I told you the truth. I delivered on my word. So, when are you gonna deliver on yours?<br />
Liz: We&#8217;ve been over this. You help me eliminate Berlin, and as far as I&#8217;m concerned, this whole thing is over. Until then, enjoy the view.<br />
Tom: Liz you can&#8217;t keep me in here! Liz! You can&#8217;t keep me in here! Damn it, Liz! </p>
<p>Liz: Sevan Volkov! Thank you for meeting with me.<br />
Volkov: And what choice did I have?<br />
Liz: Berlin. I know you supply him with arms shipments.<br />
Volkov: And how do you know this?<br />
Liz: Tell me where to find him.<br />
Volkov: If you know anything about Berlin, you know I can&#8217;t do that.<br />
Liz: Thought you might say that, which is why I nominated you for our &#8220;Most Wanted&#8221; list. C.I.D.<br />
has approved it. We&#8217;re just waiting for the Director&#8217;s signature.<br />
Volkov: Eh, if you&#8217;re gonna arrest me, arrest me.<br />
Liz: So you can sit silent in a cell with an expensive attorney? Mm, I&#8217;d rather leave you out there, let the world know we&#8217;re looking for you. Once news of this hits the streets, Berlin will know the U.S. government is spending limitless resources and time looking for you a man who has intimate details about him and his business affairs. You have two options either you lead me to Berlin or I lead Berlin to you.</p>
<p><b>Red:</b> How exactly did you come upon this information?<br />
Liz: A C.I., someone the Bureau trusts.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I don&#8217;t believe you. If the Bureau had a lead, they&#8217;d follow it. You came to this on your own, and you&#8217;re hiding it from them, coming to me instead. You&#8217;d rather see Berlin dead than arrested.<br />
Liz: Berlin killed Meera. He nearly killed Cooper. He put Tom into my life. So if you&#8217;re asking if I&#8217;m okay with a lethal outcome, damn right I am. Yeah.<br />
<b>Red:</b> If you hadn&#8217;t told me you&#8217;d killed Tom, I might think he was your source.<br />
Liz: But I did kill him.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Of course you did.<br />
Liz: Let me know when Volkov gets a time and location on Berlin.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;ll be there with bells on.</p>
<p>Samar: What&#8217;s going on?<br />
Aram: D.O.D. discovered a hidden surveillance camera at their Annapolis field office during a routine sweep.<br />
Samar: How is that relevant to us?<br />
Aram: Technology was Iranian.<br />
Samar: What were they recording?<br />
Aram: Okay, uh, the camera was placed outside the building with eyes to the front entrance. It was relaying a live stream to some off-site location. If I reactivate it, I should be able to triangulate the location where the feed&#8217;s being transmitted. Um. Oh, man. I almost forgot. [ covers camera aperture on computer ] In case someone&#8217;s watching on the other end. [ Whistles ] Okay. Camera is live. Okay, RDF is up. Signal strength looks good. Oh, accounting for time lag. [ Beeping ] And we have a lock. It&#8217;s a property just outside New Carrollton, and it looks like it&#8217;s a construction site.</p>
<p>Man: FBI! Clear! Clear! Trailer&#8217;s secure.<br />
Ressler: Lock it down. I want eyes on all access points. So, where the hell is everyone?<br />
Liz: No idea. But could this be the man they were surveilling? Jonathan Reese.<br />
Agent Jonathan Everett Reese, Defense Security Services.<br />
They&#8217;ve got everything on this guy ‚Äì addresses, phone numbers, employment history. DSS is the division tasked with protecting our nuclear scientists. They&#8217;re logging his movements. Probably trying to find the most vulnerable point of attack.<br />
It&#8217;s the DSS shuttle stop. He takes the train back from Annapolis every afternoon. He&#8217;ll be at the park-n-ride off Route50. We got to get there before they do.</p>
<p>[ Siren wailing, car alarm chirps ] [ Tires screech ]<br />
Liz or Res: Jonathan Reese FBI!<br />
Reese: What&#8217;s this about?<br />
We need to move quickly. I&#8217;ll explain in the car.<br />
[ Gunshots ] [ Air hisses ]<br />
Ressler: Shooter&#8217;s on the ridge! I don&#8217;t have eyes!<br />
[ Gunshots ] [ Tires squealing, engine revving ] [ Tires screech ]<br />

<p>[ Engine revving ] [ Tires screeching ] [ Distorted voices ]<br />
Aram: Sir, I think we have a problem. I can&#8217;t reach Agents Keen or Ressler.<br />
Cooper: Send a team to their last location. Find out what the hell is going on.</p>
<p>[ Liz wakes up in a hospital room, her arm in a cast. Ressler is in a bed across the room, asleep ]<br />
[ Ringing ] [ Monitor beeping ] [ Groans ]<br />
Scimitar: Take it easy, Agent Keen. [ Breathes deeply ] You&#8217;re at Bethesda. I&#8217;m Dr. Rivera. You and your partner were in an accident.<br />

Scimitar: Agent Ressler suffered significant head trauma in the crash. He&#8217;s had a C.T. scan. Radiology will take him for an M.R.I. shortly.<br />

Scimitar: I&#8217;m sorry? Nobody else was transported from the scene.<br />
Liz: No, no, no, no, but he was in the car.<br />
Scimitar: I&#8217;m the attending on duty. No one else was brought in.<br />
Liz: [Sighs] I need a phone. [Groans] Listen ‚Äì<br />
Scimitar: Easy.<br />
Liz: ‚Äì That crash was no accident.<br />
Scimitar: Understood. I&#8217;ll have one brought in right away.<br />
[Sighs] [Beeping continues] </p>
<p>Aram: We&#8217;re seeing multiple 911 calls within the last hour. They all report a black S.U.V. overturned just under a mile from where they picked up Reese. Cross-reference with local police activity. Two passengers were pulled from the wreck and evac&#8217;d by ambulance to Bethesda National.<br />
Only two?<br />
A man and a woman.<br />
We have to assume that&#8217;s Agent Keen and either Ressler or the D.O.D. employee.<br />
Meaning what one of them didn&#8217;t survive the crash?<br />
Cooper: Agent Navabi, I want you there as soon as possible. I&#8217;ll update Mullen at D.O.D.<br />
Here you go.<br />
Thank you.<br />
[Breathes deeply] </p>
<p>[Dialing] [Ringing]<br />
Cooper: Assistant Director Cooper.<br />
Liz: It&#8217;s me.<br />
Cooper: Agent Keen. You have no idea how good it is to hear your voice. Are you okay?<br />
Liz: Yeah, I&#8217;m fine, but, uh Ressler he&#8217;s hurt. The Iranians have John Reese. I heard some men&#8217;s voices before I passed out. They were speaking Farsi. Someone needs to find Professor Collins. The D.O.D. needs to cancel that speech and put her in protective custody now.<br />
Cooper: I&#8217;ve already alerted the D.O.D. I&#8217;m heading to the event site myself to make sure she&#8217;s on lockdown. Agent Keen, the Neurology team at Bethesda&#8217;s one of the best. They&#8217;ll take good care of Ressler. Agent Navabi&#8217;s on her way to you. Get some rest.</p>
<p>[Breathes deeply]<br />
Cooper: Thanks for coming.<br />
Assistant Director: I got your message.<br />
Cooper: John Reese was abducted by the Iranians a little over an hour ago. We need to pull Professor Collins, and I need anything you can give me on Reese ‚Äì so we can get to him ‚Äì<br />

Assistant Director: Thought it might be an alias, but it&#8217;s not. He doesn&#8217;t exist.</p>
<p>Aram: Uh, sir? Just got off the phone with Bethesda National. Uh, the hospital has no record of Agents Keen or Ressler being brought in.<br />
Cooper: I just spoke to her.</p>
<p>Nurse: How&#8217;s everything in here?<br />
Liz: Okay.<br />
Nurse: You&#8217;re doing okay, hon?<br />
Liz: [Sighs] Yeah. What happened to Radiology? They were gonna take him for another scan.<br />
Nurse: Oh, well, I&#8217;m sure someone will be down soon. He&#8217;s your partner, isn&#8217;t he? I understand. I&#8217;ll call them right now.</p>
<p>[ When nurse leaves, Liz gets up to check Ressler, sees his chart is just blank paper ]</p>
<p>Nurse: Ma&#8217;am, A-Agent Keen, you can&#8217;t be up.<br />
Liz: [ Acting groggy ] No we need to get the radiologist now!<br />
Nurse: Oh, o-okay. [Sighs] Okay, you&#8217;re fine. You&#8217;re all right. Oh, I&#8217;m sorry. We need to get Radiology in. Let&#8217;s get you back in bed. You&#8217;re fine.<br />
Liz: Okay. Oh, my gosh, I&#8217;m so sorry! I&#8217;m so sorry.<br />
Nurse: It&#8217;s all right. You just relax.<br />
Liz: We need to get Radiology.<br />
Nurse: Okay, take it easy. Take it easy.<br />
Liz: Thank you.</p>
<p>Zo√´ [ Exhales sharply ]: I never eat anchovies unless I don&#8217;t know I&#8217;m eating them. [ Both chuckle ] But I have to say, this is pretty delicious.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Anchovies get a bad rap. Try the wine.<br />
Zo√´: It would be better with beer.<br />
<b>Red:</b>[Laughs] It might very well be better with beer.<br />

<b>Red:</b> I do, a daughter.<br />
Zo√´: The two of you close?<br />
<b>Red:</b> It&#8217;s complicated.<br />
Zo√´: She doesn&#8217;t like anchovies?<br />
<b>Red:</b>[ Chuckles ] You know, I don&#8217;t know about that. [ Sniffs ] I wish it were that simple.<br />
Zo√´: My father ‚Äì he and I ‚Äì My father did things I hated him for. Things that were unforgivable. [ Sniffles ]<br />

Zo√´: I haven&#8217;t seen my father in a long long time.<br />
[ Zoe breathes deeply, realizes something is wrong, searches Red&#8217;s eyes ]<br />
Zo√´: What have you done?<br />

[ Breathing deeply ] [ She whimpers ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m not gonna hurt you.<br />
[ Gasping ] [ Whimpers ] [ Dembe pulls up. They lift her in. Car door closes ] </p>
<p>Cooper: We got played. The Scimitar created John Reese. Which means we didn&#8217;t find that construction trailer. We were led there. Everything in that trailer was designed to make us think John Reese was DSS.<br />
Why?<br />
Cooper: So when we lost him, we would think the identity of our scientist was in jeopardy.<br />
This was all done to trigger a reaction. They isolated Keen and Ressler, made them believe that losing Reese was a threat to national security. This was all a con done to expose Amalia Collins.<br />
So, where the heck is Agents Keen and Ressler? </p>
<p>Liz [ on phone to Cooper ]: Someone needs to find Professor Collins. The D.O.D. needs to cancel that speech and put her in protective custody now.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />

<p>[Grunting] [Breathes deeply] [Exhales sharply] [Door closes] [Sighs]<br />

Liz: [Grunts] [Grunts] You tell me what&#8217;s in the syringe [Grunting] or I will stick it in you and find out for myself.<br />

Liz: What&#8217;s in his I.V.? [Grunts]<br />
Nurse: Same thing.<br />
Liz:  Okay, who are you? Where is this hospital?<br />
Nurse: Doctor!<br />
Liz: Aah! [Gasping] Ressler? Ressler? Ressler? Ressler? Ressler? Can you hear me? We got to get the hell out of here! </p>
<p>Samar: They&#8217;re definitely not at Bethesda.</p>
<p>Aram: Cooper went to secure Professor Collins. Uh, I traced the call Liz made to Cooper&#8217;s cell.<br />
Their rerouting and encryption are incredibly sophisticated. This is gonna take hours to untangle.<br />
Samar: Okay, so, what&#8217;s next?<br />
Aram: Cooper&#8217;s pulled six teams from other assignments. He sent them ‚Äì<br />
<b>Red:</b> [Beep] Hello? Dembe, it&#8217;s Agent Navabi. We have a situation. [Radio chatter] [Grunts] Come on. We got to go now.</p>
<p>[ Red and Samar in car ]<br />
Samar: It&#8217;s been over two hours. I don&#8217;t need to tell you his reputation. Once he has the intelligence he needs ‚Äì<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yes, I know, Agent Navabi. Tell me about this lead of yours.<br />
Samar: He&#8217;s not my lead. His name is Ali Hassan. He&#8217;s the target of a major Mossad initiative.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I have a slight but memorable acquaintance with Mr. Hassan.<br />
Samar: Mossad has been tracking his movements for months. My superiors believe he&#8217;s the key to unraveling a dozen covert Iranian opts. But you think he knows where to find The Scimitar.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Perhaps. Mossad has no tolerance for any agenda except Mossad&#8217;s. You&#8217;ll be sanctioned for this indiscretion.<br />
Samar: So be it. I can&#8217;t work with this task force unless my partners are my highest priority. So this has become quite personal.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I understand. But you may have an even more personal stake in this case ‚Äì than perhaps you realize.<br />
Samar: And why is that?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Because one of The Scimitar&#8217;s little-known aliases is Walid Abu Sitta.<br />
Samar: Walid Abu Sitta is the man who ordered the bombing that killed my brother.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yes. That&#8217;s why I brought this case to you.</p>
<p>Hassan: [ Groans softly ] There. [ Indistinct talking in distance ] [ Classical music playing ] [ Glass shatters in distance ] What was that? You hear that? [ Thud ] Fareed, what&#8217;s going on?! [ Thud ] Fareed?! [ Golf club strikes ball ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Hassan! I love this club!<br />
Hassan: Son of a bitch!<br />
<b>Red:</b> Carbon fiber?<br />
Hassan: Reddington, stop! ‚Äì Ooh! ‚Äì Stop!  [Glass shatters] Damn it! What have you done with my guard?!<br />
<b>Red:</b> Fareed is taking a rest.<br />
[Sighs]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Keep your plum covered. We&#8217;re not alone.<br />
Samar: [Gun cocks] I&#8217;ll take your weapon.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;ve always regretted sparing your life that night in the Strait Of Hormuz. But I see pity has its rewards. Live and learn. You&#8217;ve been very careless, Ali.</p>
<p>Samar: My unit has been surveilling you for months, and the intelligence we&#8217;ve gathered has been very helpful ‚Äì so helpful that I fully expect to be disciplined for coming here without authorization. Just by being here, I have everything and, therefore, nothing to lose.<br />
Hassan: What do you want?<br />
<b>Red:</b> The Scimitar. My friend here thinks you may know where to find him. He would&#8217;ve needed support when he got to the States. I&#8217;m guessing that support came from you.I know what you must be thinking, Ali. Imagine your future, the rest of your life spent in a dismal Israeli prison, some dark hole they put you in, bending your fingers and pulling your toes until they forget you ever existed. Think carefully, Ali, because, as you are my witness, that future will seem very bright, indeed, if you don&#8217;t tell us what we want to know.<br />
Hassan: [Sighs] He did make contact. Asked to use one of my warehouses. Said he needed building supplies. For what, I don&#8217;t know.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Tell me about this warehouse.</p>
<p>[Grunts softly] [Indistinct talking] Keen! [Grunts] [Gunshot]<br />

<h3 id="decembrist">üî¥ 2:8 The Decembrist</h3>

<h3>Script: 2:8 The Decembrist</h3>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<i><b>Blurb:</b> Red and Berlin head to Moscow looking for The Decembrist, who falsely blamed Red for murdering Berlin&#8217;s daughter. Alan Fitch tells Red he will be in trouble with his alliance (later called &#8220;The Cabal&#8221;) if he does not possess The Fulcrum. Red confronts Liz about Tom.</i></p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<b>Voiceover: Previously on The Blacklist</b></p>
<p>[Two gunshots]<br />
Liz: No.<br />
<b>Red:</b> We can&#8217;t leave him alive.<br />
Liz: Please go. I&#8217;ll finish it. This is between us.<br />

You&#8217;re gonna do whatever you&#8217;re gonna do. You always have. Just do me one favor. Look me in the eyes when you do it.</p>
<p><b>Red:</b> Your daughter told me your name is Milosz Kirchhoff. All these years, Mr. Kirchhoff, you&#8217;ve believed with the blackest of hearts that I murdered your daughter. And yet here she is. The story was wrong, Milosz. Please enlighten me. What were you told and who did the telling?<br />
Berlin/Kirchhoff: It was in &#8217;91. The Soviet union was falling apart. A small group of us. Members of the Politburo, the military, KGB, Stasi. Had a plan to push back the progressives, to stem the tide. We were meeting and discussing strategy when a bomb.<br />
<b>Red:</b> The Kursk Bombing.<br />
Berlin/Kirchhoff: Fifteen died. And with them, our resistance. Rumors began that the Americans were involved. One name emerged. Yours. You came after my daughter. You exposed her as a dissident. She went to jail. After that, my loyalty was questioned. I was exiled to the Gulag, where, one by one, her bones were sent to me. [he says, looking at Zo√´]<br />
<b>Red:</b> You fled. You must have had help. Who?<br />
Zo√´: There was a man. He said he could protect me from. From you.<br />
<b>Red:</b> What was his name?<br />
Zo√´: I never met him. I don&#8217;t know. His people. They called him &#8220;The Decembrist.&#8221; Please. That&#8217;s all I know.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Zo√´ [to Berlin]: You killed my friends. You destroyed my life once. Isn&#8217;t that enough?<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />

<b>Red:</b> The Decembrist.</p>
<p>Samoan: We can&#8217;t let him walk out of here.<br />

Liz: Close that door. Keep him quiet.</p>
<p>Harbormaster: Whoa! Easy! Harbormaster. Put the gun down.<br />
Liz: All right.<br />

[Music continues]<br />
Brimley: Fella won&#8217;t talk!<br />

Liz: What the hell is going on?!<br />
<b>Red:</b> We&#8217;re shaking a few trees. There&#8217;s been a development. It seems Berlin is merely a pawn who&#8217;s been tragically manipulated.<br />
Liz: Manipulated by who?<br />
<b>Red:</b> That&#8217;s what Brimley&#8217;s trying to ascertain.<br />
Liz: Berlin killed Meera, he put Tom in my life, and every time you have a chance to stop him, you let him go.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Berlin will be held accountable for his actions after I acquire the name of the man who set him against me, a man they call The Decembrist. If you want to find the one ultimately responsible for gutting Harold Cooper and killing Meera Malik, I suggest you help me find him.</p>
<p>Liz: The man we&#8217;re looking for is known as The Decembrist. His acts are said to have contributed to the end of communism in Eastern Europe.<br />

<h3 id="braxton">üî¥ 2:9 Luther Braxton</h3>

 <b>üî¥ Script: 2:9 Luther Braxton </b></p>

Last updated: 8/8/2015<br />
Program originally aired 2/1/2015 in the US<br />

<h3>Script 2:9 Luther Braxton Part 1</h3>
<div align="left">
&nbsp;</p>
<p><i><b>Blurb:</b> Red allows himself to be captured so he will be &#8220;disappeared&#8221; to a secret U.S. prison in the Bering Sea where a thief named Luther Braxton is planning to break into secret government computers containing information on the Fulcrum. First part of two. </i> </p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<blockquote><p>
Several TV news people: We are just now getting word of a story developing out of Hong Kong. Sources say authorities there have apprehended legendary criminal Raymond Reddington. He&#8217;s been on the FBI&#8217;s Most Wanted list longer than any other fugitive, but tonight, sources are confirming Reddington was arrested in Hong Kong just hours ago. Reddington was once a rising star at the Pentagon. Sources say he was being groomed for admiral when, on Christmas Eve, 1990, while on his way home to visit his wife and daughter, Reddington vanished.<br />
Reporter: Four years later, Reddington resurfaced and was charged with treason in absentia for selling top-secret American intelligence to foreign states.
</p></blockquote>
<p>Prison guard: From this point forward, you don&#8217;t exist.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ Chuckling ] Oh, that&#8217;s a load off.<br />
[ Tires squeal ] </p>
<blockquote><p>
Reporter #2: Just hours ago, the US State Department confirmed Reddington has been remanded into US custody, but officials will not comment on his current location.
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ ‚ô´  thruppence and sixpence each day too much, magic bus<br />
&#8217;cause I drive my baby every way too much, magic bus [ Song ends ]</p>
<p>Cooper: Reddington&#8217;s off the radar.<br />
Liz: What do you mean?<br />
Cooper: We don&#8217;t know where Reddington is? CIA&#8217;s not saying.<br />
Liz: Why not? Reddington&#8217;s our asset.<br />
Cooper: Only 41 people in the US government know that. I&#8217;ve talked to all of them. Nobody knows where he is.<br />
Samar: He&#8217;s been on the run for 25 years. His arrest was bound to happen.<br />
Ressler: No, Reddington moves too fluidly to get caught up in something as obvious as a public assassination in Hong Kong. No, he wanted this to happen.<br />
Liz: What if he didn&#8217;t?<br />
Aram: Why would Mr. Reddington want to get captured?<br />
Navabi: His arrest happened overseas. We have to assume he wanted proximity to something.<br />
Ressler: Well, if he&#8217;s grabbed, it&#8217;s either by the CIA ground branch or JSOC.<br />
Liz: You think it&#8217;s an intelligence apparatus that&#8217;s holding him?<br />
Cooper: Scrub our sources at Langley, and do it fast. Once they drop him in whatever hole he&#8217;s headed for he&#8217;s not coming back.</p>
<p>[ Door shuts ]<br />
Guard: You speak when you&#8217;re spoken to.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Call the number. Ask for a houseman. Call the number. $50,000 will be transferred into the account of your choice. $50,000. All I want is two minutes with your warden.<br />
[ Door opens ] </p>
<p>Ressler: All right. We found him.<br />
Man: Hey.<br />
Ressler: Hey. We got him. CIA analyst at Langley confirmed they&#8217;re holding Reddington at an off-book lockdown called The Factory.<br />
Samar: That&#8217;s bad news. That&#8217;s really bad news.<br />
Aram: That place is real?<br />
Liz: The Factory? Wait, what&#8217;s The Factory?<br />
Cooper: It&#8217;s a level-10 detention facility specifically designed to process detainees who&#8217;ve been trained to withstand interrogation and torture. Assets are brought in, information is squeezed out ‚Äì data, intel, anything that may be of value.<br />
Aram: This place is a slaughterhouse for spies.<br />
Cooper: They reduce them to ones and zeroes. What&#8217;s left is a husk that either rots away behind bars or is executed outright.<br />
Liz: We&#8217;ve got to get him out of there.<br />
Ressler: You think the CIA&#8217;s gonna let us talk to him, just walk right in there? No.<br />
Liz: He&#8217;s our asset.<br />
Samar: No, they&#8217;re gonna keep him all to themselves.<br />
Cooper: If he went to this factory on purpose, I suspect it was to make contact with somebody he couldn&#8217;t get to on the outside. Reddington gave up 25 years of freedom to see this guy. I want to know who he is and what intel he&#8217;s got that&#8217;s so damned important.</p>
<p>Warden: Mast Sergeant Desmond says you offered him a bribe. Care to explain?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Within 12 hours, inmate Luther Todd Braxton will break out of his cell. When he does, he will steal a classified intelligence packet that contains secrets vital to your National Security. The means for his escape and his team are already in place.<br />
Warden: This story feels like a desperate last gasp from a dying man.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Could be. Regardless, if you don&#8217;t move quickly, the prison will be overrun and the dozens of innocent men and women who operate this facility will be subdued and executed, beginning with you.<br />
Warden: Luther Braxton is in solitary.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Not for long.</p>
<p>[ Machinery whirring ] [ Electricity crackling ] [ Whirring and crackling stop ]<br />
Man: He&#8217;s not cooperating. Take him back to his cell. We go again in two hours.<br />
[ Joints cracking. Guard slips a wire component into Braxton&#8217;s mouth ] </p>
<p>Goodson: Agent Cooper, Kat Goodson. As you know, the Director has brought me here to liaison with your task force.<br />
Cooper: Of course. We&#8217;ve met ‚Äì the correspondents&#8217; dinner.<br />
Goodson: Ah. You were the scotch ‚Äì neat? Please, tell us what you know.<br />
Cooper: I&#8217;m not at liberty to say.<br />
Goodson: The clandestine service is aware of the arrangement your task force has with Reddington. It&#8217;s why we&#8217;re running point through your office.<br />
Cooper: Well, then perhaps the Director should&#8217;ve notified me before sending Reddington to The Factory.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
The Director: The section chief sent a cable from the warden. Said that Raymond Reddington claims that a detainee, one Luther Braxton, poses a National Security threat, and we&#8217;re hoping that you can tell us something about their connection.<br />
Cooper: I don&#8217;t know. Who&#8217;s Luther Braxton? </p>
<p>Liz: Braxton is a thief. Interpol&#8217;s been hunting him for years. He plans his heists to occur in the midst of chaos. He is organized, meticulous, and he is bloody.<br />
Aram: He stole $282 million from Baghdad in the middle of Operation Shock And Awe, abducted a CIA asset out of Iran during the &#8217;09 election protests. Later, he sold his secrets to Beijing.<br />
Ressler: The CIA announced his death two months ago.<br />
Goodson: We say that about a lot of the inmates at The Factory. Truth is Braxton&#8217;s being interrogated for secrets he stole from the Chinese, from the Iranians, us.<br />
Ressler: Well, my money&#8217;s on the fact that these two have a history together. Reddington, Braxton ‚Äì they&#8217;re planning something.<br />
Cooper: Whatever it is, you&#8217;re going to find out.<br />
Liz: Oh, we don&#8217;t have authorization.<br />
Goodson: You do now. Get to Reddington. Find out what he&#8217;s up to.</p>
<p>Guard: Hey, Braxton, chow! [ Alarm blaring ] </p>
<p>Guard 2: We have a Code Oscar, block &#8220;B,&#8221; dorm six! Activate critical response! We need an emergency response team in block &#8220;B&#8221; now! </p>
<p>Guard 3: [ Indistinct shouting ] Get away from the door! Fire one! Hands‚Äì hands up! Get on the ground! [ Gunfire ] Aah!! </p>
<p>[ Handcuffs clicking ]<br />

<b>Red:</b> I tried. It&#8217;s too late. You&#8217;ve lost your facility.<br />
warden: No, you tell me I&#8217;m gonna have an escape before it happens. Now you&#8217;re getting evac&#8217;d out?<br />

Guards: We got a problem. ERF failed.<br />

[ Blaring continues ] [ Beeping ]<br />

[ Beeping, heavy clang ] </p>
<p>[ In helicopter ]<br />

<p>Man: Horrible, isn&#8217;t it‚Äì this room‚Äì this is where all the prisoners come to die. After you break their minds. They&#8217;re led here like cattle for you to slaughter.<br />

<p>Goodson: This is Agent Rosenberg. He&#8217;s our hostage negotiator.<br />

Rosenberg: Understood, and they&#8217;re gonna be fine. We&#8217;re gonna take our time, hear what he has to say, and get everyone out alive.<br />
You ready? [ Beeping ] Mr. Braxton, this is Agent Phillip Rosenberg. The Director of NCS has instructed me to open a dialogue with you.<br />
Braxton: We&#8217;re not having a dialogue.<br />
Rosenberg: I&#8217;m here to listen, but first, I just need to talk to the warden. I just need to make sure that he&#8217;s okay and can confirm the hostages are okay.<br />
Braxton: No, you are a water boy, a bureaucrat with a stack of cue cards.<br />
Rosenberg: Just need to talk to the warden.<br />
Braxton: Of course you do ‚Äì protocol. I have him right here.<br />
Warden: This is Warden Mills.<br />
Rosenberg: Mr. Mills, everyone&#8217;s okay?<br />
Warden: Some casualties, but all accounted for.<br />
Rosenberg: That&#8217;s terrific. Glad to hear your voice. See that, Mr. Braxton? I just wanted to talk to the warden.<br />
[ Braxton shoots him ]<br />
Rosenberg: Mr. Mills? Warden? Mr. Mills?<br />
Braxton: I&#8217;m done talking to you, Mr. Rosenberg. I want to speak to somebody with real authority.<br />
Cooper: This is Harold Cooper, Assistant Director for the FBI.<br />
Braxton: Hello, Harold Cooper. I&#8217;m pretty sure you see how this works. I get what I need, or somebody dies. From here on forward I am the warden.</p>
<p>[ Someone approaches Liz, grabs her from behind ]<br />
Liz: [ Gasps ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> What the hell are you doing here?<br />
Liz. I came to help get you out.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You came out of curiosity.<br />
Liz: Or maybe I actually care about what happens to you.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Your government is being robbed.<br />
Liz: From here? How? What&#8217;s he after?<br />
<b>Red:</b> The Fulcrum.<br />
Liz: I don&#8217;t know what that is. The Fulcrum‚Äì What is that?<br />
<b>Red:</b> It&#8217;s a blackmail file‚Äì proof of the existence of an extraordinarily powerful clandestine organization. If their activities were made public, some of the most powerful and influential men would go to prison or be executed.<br />
Liz: And it&#8217;s here, this Fulcrum?<br />
<b>Red:</b> No, the Fulcrum isn&#8217;t here, but I believe information critical to finding it is, and that&#8217;s what Braxton wants.I&#8217;m here to stop it.<br />
Liz: I can help you.<br />
<b>Red:</b> No, you need to leave.<br />
Liz: Ressler and Samar have been taken hostage.<br />
<b>Red:</b> They shouldn&#8217;t even be here. You never should&#8217;ve come here.<br />
Liz: Why didn&#8217;t you come to us? What aren&#8217;t you telling me? Why don&#8217;t you want me here?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;ll get to Ressler and Samar as soon as I can, but you need to get back on that chopper.<br />
Liz; Not without Ressler and Samar or you. Now, how are we gonna stop Braxton? He has an entire team.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Well, sadly, there isn&#8217;t a prison on Earth where I don&#8217;t know a few guys. </p>
<p>Man [ British accent ]: If Braxton wants to access the secrets they beat out of us, he&#8217;s gonna need to get into the server, which is only accessible from the Nest.<br />
<b>Red:</b> How about during a lockdown?<br />
Man: This facility&#8217;s like a submarine. It&#8217;s compartmentalized. It can only be shut down by sections. The security protocols render the entire server room completely inaccessible.<br />
Desmond: How the hell do you know that? I didn&#8217;t know that.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Khan has broken out of seven prisons. This will be eight.<br />
Liz: This server room ‚Äì where is it?<br />
Man: Northwest quadrant, basement.mWe can&#8217;t get you inside, but the German ‚Äì he has an idea.<br />
German: [ German accent ] Who is she? Who is this girl?<br />
<b>Red:</b> She&#8217;s with me. Your idea?<br />
German: The boiler room. It&#8217;s located next to the server room. If you could get there, you could reprogram it to overload. The pressure would cause an explosion.<br />
Liz: That would blow up the server room?<br />
German: If you&#8217;re lucky, you&#8217;ll take out the server room. If you&#8217;re unlucky, the whole prison craters.<br />

British: Yes, the only way into the boiler room undetected is through a single air duct that&#8217;s less than 24 inches square.<br />
Liz: [ Sighs ] Looks like I&#8217;m the tunnel rat.<br />
<b>Red:</b> All right. Khan will guide you to the boiler room. Gernert and I will be waiting for you to let us in, then you&#8217;ll reprogram the system.<br />
German: Good.<br />
Man on couch: What about me? What&#8217;s my job?<br />
<b>Red:</b> You don&#8217;t have a job. You&#8217;re here because of what your cartel did to Felix Moralez and my people in Reynosa. [ Shoots him ] Okay. Shall we go to work? </p>
<p>Man: [ Beeping ] Braxton, you need to see this.</p>
<p>[ Telephone ringing ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m sorry. The warden can&#8217;t get to the phone right now. May I please take a message? Nothing? Not a &#8220;Hello, how are you?&#8221; Say something, Luther.<br />
Braxton: Reddington.<br />
<b>Red:</b> That&#8217;s me.<br />
Braxton: You&#8217;re locked out, Red. I have complete control over this hellhole.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m confident you&#8217;ve got a plan for every imaginable scenario, but it&#8217;s the scenarios you can&#8217;t imagine that bite you in the ass, Luther, like me here.<br />
Braxton: Do you think this is something that snuck up on me? After Belgrade?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Ah. Belgrade. Boy, things got nasty in Belgrade, didn&#8217;t they?<br />
Braxton: It&#8217;s funny‚Äì up until then, I was aimless, just an ordinary thief, but after Belgrade, I became known as the man who bested the great Ray Reddington.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You didn&#8217;t best me, Luther. You butchered and clawed your way into my pockets, and innocent people died in the process.<br />
Braxton: You&#8217;re such a snob, Red. Always considered yourself above the fray with your handmade suits and your fancy wine, your private jets. Do you even drive? You got everybody convinced you&#8217;re so hard, Red, but I know better. You&#8217;re soft.<br />
<b>Red:</b>You&#8217;re not getting the Fulcrum.<br />
Braxton: And how you gonna stop me, Red? Bore me to death with Beethoven? Put me to sleep quoting Nietzsche? Come on. We both know that in order to stop me, you got to have balls. You got to run the gauntlet. And after Belgrade, well that&#8217;s just not gonna happen. So, tell me ‚Äì how are you gonna stop me, Red?<br />
<b>Red:</b> &#8220;A wise man can learn more from a foolish question than a fool can learn from a wise answer.&#8221;<br />
Braxton: Was that Nietzsche?<br />
<b>Red:</b> No. Bruce Lee.</p>
<p>Samar: This man has an abdominal wound. He&#8217;s going to die.<br />
Ressler: Let him down. Damn it, let him down! </p>
<p>[ Door opens ]<br />
Braxton: Okay, Harold, let&#8217;s test your reflexes. This entire facility has been put into lockdown meaning that all existing codes that ran this prison have been invalidated.<br />
Cooper: We&#8217;re aware of that.<br />
Braxton: Good, then you must also be aware that one single code has been generated by the mainframe ‚Äì a master code giving the CIA and any rescue units all access. I want it.<br />
Cooper: Understood. I can get my people working on that right away.<br />
Braxton: Okay. Your reflexes, Harold‚Äì shabby. Mine, however‚Äì lightning quick. [ Shoots woman ] You just cost an innocent woman her life, which means we&#8217;ll just have to go get ourselves another one. Let me set the scene for you, just like them old radio dramas your granny used to listen to. I&#8217;m standing in front of a tall, fit very attractive Persian girl by the name of Samar Navabi. Maybe you&#8217;re familiar with her. Anyway, Miss Navabi has a noose around her neck‚Äì her very long, lovely neck, which is about to get a lot longer unless you give me the code. I&#8217;ll give you 10 minutes.<br />
Aram: We&#8217;re gonna give the code, right? Sir, I&#8217;m sorry, but you have to give the code. It&#8217;s a black site. Nobody will know we&#8217;re negotiating.<br />
Cooper: I&#8217;m sorry, but‚Äì<br />
Aram: We&#8217;re gonna give the code!</p>
<p>Cooper: I am not allowing that maniac to lynch one of my agents.<br />
Goodson: You can&#8217;t give him the code. You know the protocol.<br />
Cooper: The minute that that negotiator got here, he gave me all the relevant details on the factory, including the master code. Why wouldn&#8217;t I give it to him?<br />
Goodson: Braxton doesn&#8217;t want the code to break out of prison. He wants it to break into our network.<br />
Cooper: What network?<br />
Goodson: The factory isn&#8217;t just a black site. It&#8217;s a level-six intelligence node. It communicates directly with Langley, the Pentagon, the White House sit room. The intel being squeezed out of these targets, our highest-level targets, is mission-critical. We needed our interrogators and our operatives in the field working together in real time, so we removed any latency between the time we received a lead and our ability to act on it.<br />
Cooper: You put an access point to the country&#8217;s most sensitive data in a prison with the country&#8217;s most dangerous enemies?<br />
Goodson: Yes. Which is why I am asking you‚Äì do not release that code.<br />
[ Knock on door ]<br />

Cooper: Cooper.<br />

Cooper: If I give it to you, what assurance do I have that no hostages will be harmed?<br />

[ Machinery whirring ] [ Choking and gasping ]<br />
Braxton: You hear that sound, Harold?<br />
[ Choking and gasping continue ]<br />
Braxton: That&#8217;s the sound of Agent Navabi&#8217;s neck being broken.<br />
Samar: Please. Stop.<br />

<h3>Script 2:10 Luther Braxton ‚Äì Conclusion</h3>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<i><b>Blurb:</b> Convinced she can lead him to the Fulcrum, Luther Braxton has captured Liz and is going to use a doctor to retrieve her memories. Red is hot on his trail. He too wants to know what she remembers about a fire when she was 4 years old. Second part of two.</i></p>

[The black site has been hit by a missile]<br />
[ Air rushing and whistling ] [ Breathing heavily ] [ Gunshots ] [ Metal clanging ] [ Grunting ]</i><br />
Ressler: Hang on, hang on! You&#8217;re not gonna die today. Hang on.<br />
[ Gasps ] [ Panting ] [ Groans ]<br />
Ressler: Okay, okay. Come here.<br />
[ Coughs ]<br />

<p>Cooper: What do we have?<br />

Goodson: I have no authorization to dispatch the Coast Guard.<br />
Cooper: My people are on that rig.<br />
Goodson: That rig was a level-10 detention facility. It does not exist. It never existed.<br />

<p>Ressler: Reddington! Where&#8217;s Keen?<br />
<b><b>Red:</b></b> Braxton took her.<br />

<p>Voice from helicopter: We&#8217;re on final approach. We need a head count on survivors.<br />

[ Bad guy &#8216;s gun cocks, to Red: ] You&#8217;re not going anywhere.<br />
[ Desmond shoots bad guy ]<br />
Desmond: Let&#8217;s go.</p>
<p>[ Liz is being waterboarded; whimpers ]<br />

[ Muffled whimpers, screams ] </p>
<p>Orchard: What do you want?<br />

<p>Braxton: The princess here has something in her head that I want. It&#8217;s a memory. Now, you helped make all my memories go away. You made Khafji disappear. Boom!
