Come hold me &#8216;neath the water&#8217;s skin until I&#8217;m new again<br />
And I said what I was thinking: now you can&#8217;t see what&#8217;s good &#8217;til it&#8217;s gone<br />
Then there&#8217;s something to be said for a place to lay your head&#8230;</i></p>
<p>Dr. Orchard: Thank you for meeting me.<br />
Liz: You said it was urgent?<br />
Orchard: I didn&#8217;t mean to alarm you, but I thought you should know that during the RM Therapy, when you were under, I saw something.<br />
Liz: So, what? What does that mean?<br />
Orchard: Based on how you responded Liz, I don&#8217;t think I&#8217;m the first one who&#8217;s looked into your memory.<br />
Liz: No. I&#8217;ve never been treated.<br />
Orchard: You may not remember. You may have been very young. But I think someone may have tried to block your memory of that fire.<br />
Liz: [ Scoffs ] I didn&#8217;t make it up.<br />
Orchard: The people and the events may have been there, but in different roles.I know this is difficult to comprehend.<br />
Liz: Are you telling me I may never know what really happened that night?<br />
Orchard: I&#8217;m telling you that the only people who could tell you what really happened are the people who want you to forget.‚ô§</p>
<p><i>‚ô´ And, they&#8217;ll come clean us, we&#8217;ll both live again<br />

and they&#8217;ll come clean us we&#8217;ll both live again</i></p>
<p>[ Fabric ripping ] [ Liz takes her stuffed bunny and begins ripping at it, instinctively. She finds a small box (the Fulcrum?), opens it. To me it looks like a computer chip, but could be a micro-recording device, or even microfiche. (The box looks like a tiny version of the Sorrento music box that Red built.) A look of childlike happiness takes over Liz&#8217;s face&#8230; ]</p>

<h3>Script 2:11 Ruslan Denisov</h3>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<i><b>Blurb:</b> Red, Liz and Ressler travel to Uzbekistan, where the CIA has spies masquerading as clergy and is covering up the crimes of a U.S.-based oil company. The man Liz hired to guard Tom is questioned by a detective.</i></p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Men chanting in native language ] [ Church bell tolls ] [ Indistinct shouting ]<br />
Denisov: You lie.<br />
[ Breathing heavily ]<br />
Denisov: Would a simple servant of God have this? You&#8217;re no more a priest than I am. Here&#8217;s your burning bush. So talk to your God.<br />
[ Keypad beeps ] [ Ringing ]<br />
Burke: This is Burke. OP-SEC 3828. We have a situation.</p>
<p>[ Knock on door ]<br />
Mrs Susan Ames: Officer Collins.<br />
Wilcox: Martin Wilcox. We spoke on the phone.<br />
Mrs Ames: Of course. Detective, thanks for coming.<br />
Collins: Susan, this is Detective Wilcox with Metro PD. I&#8217;ve brought him up to speed.<br />
Wilcox: Mrs. Ames, we&#8217;ll do whatever we can to find your husband.<br />
Mrs Ames: Thanks. Eugene disappears sometimes to Atlantic City, once to Vegas, but he always calls, and he&#8217;s never gone for more than a few days.<br />
Wilcox: And I understand there&#8217;s some incident that happened before his absence ‚Äì<br />
Mrs Ames: Eugene came home. He said he got an anonymous tip about trespassers over by one of the marina docks. The Lieutenant went to check it out, came back about an hour later, said he got the scare of his life. He ran into an FBI agent on one of the old ships, said she pulled out a gun as he was boarding.<br />
Wilcox: An FBI agent?<br />
Mrs Ames: Said the FBI was looking for two fugitives who escaped Cumberland the night before. If something happened to Eugene, it&#8217;s got to be one of them. Don&#8217;t you think? This agent he spoke with ‚Äì<br />
Wilcox: Is there any chance your husband got a name?<br />
Mrs Ames: He did better than that. She gave him a card.<br />
Wilcox: [ Reading ] Special Agent Elizabeth Keen.</p>
<p>Aram [holds the tiny wooden box]: I&#8217;ve never seen anything like it.<br />
Liz: What is it?<br />
Aram: I don&#8217;t know. It was ‚Äì<br />
Liz: I think it contains some kind of message.<br />
Aram: Where&#8217;d you get it?<br />
Liz: I need you to see if you can figure out what it is, how it works.<br />
Aram: There are people who are far more qualified at this kind of thing than me.<br />
Liz: But none that I know and trust.<br />
[ Footsteps approaching ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> I hope I&#8217;m interrupting.<br />
Liz: Yes.<br />
Aram: No. No.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You&#8217;re not answering your phone.<br />
Liz: So leave a message.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Dembe did. Two, in fact. We have a new case, Agent Keen.<br />
Liz: Then tell Cooper.<br />
<b>Red:</b> That&#8217;s not how this works.<br />
Aram: I think I left my soup in the microwave. Lobster bisque. [leaves]<br />
Liz: I know exactly how this works. You lie, say what you need to say to make me believe you actually care ‚Äì<br />
<b>Red:</b> That&#8217;s not true.<br />
Liz: You&#8217;re after the Fulcrum. It&#8217;s why you&#8217;re here. Not to help me or protect me or whatever spin you&#8217;re selling today. Well, I&#8217;m not buying it. From this point on, there&#8217;s no reason for us to talk unless it&#8217;s about the work.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Fine. Then let&#8217;s work. I think you&#8217;ll find today&#8217;s most intriguing story on page 20, bottom-left corner.<br />
Liz: [ Reading ] &#8220;According to Uzbek authorities, Father Aleksandr Nabiyev, a local priest in the Tashkent Region of Uzbekistan&#8221;‚Äì You&#8217;re intrigued because a priest was kidnapped?<br />
<b>Red:</b> No. I&#8217;m intrigued because the priest is not a priest. From what I hear, the good Father Nabiyev is an agent of the CIA. That&#8217;s a crime, Agent Keen. Going back to the Cold War, the CIA has a long and controversial history of using religious figures as spies in violation of executive orders, internal CIA policy, and promises made by every president since Ford.<br />
Liz: And you know who kidnapped this agent?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I do. Unfortunately, he&#8217;s an associate of mine. His name is Ruslan Denisov. He commands a nasty, little band of separatists known as SRU. Translated, they are the supreme republic of a free, righteous, and independent Uzbekistan. I told Ruslan it was a bit much, but he can be quite melodramatic, not to mention violent and entirely unreasonable. Politics are his passion, and to fund his separatist agenda, he&#8217;s become something of an abduction mogul, specializing in senior executives of foreign corporations working in or passing through the region. He holds them for ransom at prices far above market standard.<br />
Man: [ Flashover ] Your company has made it clear it has no interest in paying for your release. [bang]<br />
Liz: And you do business with this man?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Don&#8217;t underestimate the usefulness of a nasty band of armed separatists. But lately, Ruslan&#8217;s been breaking promises. His temper has cost me and my partners considerably more than he&#8217;s worth.<br />
Liz: So everybody wins. You help us rescue the agent, we eliminate a thorn in your side.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Careful on this one, Lizzy. You have more than just a blacklister to worry about this time. The CIA will do whatever it takes to keep this quiet.</p>
<p>Aram: Richard Gagnon, Executive VP for a French video-component manufacturer. Here he is before he was taken [ Keyboard clacking ] and here he is the day SRU released him in exchange for $2 million cash.<br />
Liz: We have a list of over 30 victims.<br />
Samar: I don&#8217;t understand. This guy makes a fortune taking corporate execs. Now he takes a CIA agent. Why change the business model?<br />
Let&#8217;s find him and ask.<br />
Aram: I&#8217;m sorry, but people&#8217;s faith is sacred. Religion should be off-limits to spies. Wouldn&#8217;t work in my country.<br />
Yeah, well, the Agency knows the law, so they&#8217;ve gone this far, something big is going on in that area.</p>
<p>Wright: It&#8217;s a simple question, Mr. Heyworth. Is Father Nabiyev an operative of the CIA or not? Heyworth: We all know that would be illegal.<br />
Wright: That&#8217;s not an answer to my question.<br />
Heyworth: Not to my knowledge.<br />
Cooper: Look, I didn&#8217;t call this meeting to make a case against the Agency. We&#8217;re here because I have an informant who I think can help get your man back safely.<br />
Heyworth: If he were our man ‚Äì and I&#8217;m saying &#8220;If&#8221; ‚Äì the Agency would prefer to handle this on its own.<br />
Wright: If an American citizen&#8217;s been kidnapped overseas, that&#8217;s FBI jurisdiction. If he&#8217;s your asset, I can keep you involved. If not, you&#8217;re out. Agent Cooper, your task force will run point on the investigation and any hostage negotiations.<br />
Cooper: My people can leave tonight.</p>
<p>Liz: Commander Kushan. I&#8217;m Agent Keen. This is Agent Ressler. On behalf of the Bureau, we appreciate your help.<br />
Kushan: Let me be very clear, Agent Keen. It is you who are here to help me. This is an Uzbek military operation.<br />
Liz: All due respect, sir, an American citizen has been abducted.<br />
Which is why we have extended the courtesy of our invitation. But you will not be negotiating with Ruslan Denisov, and you will not be negotiating with me. And you will turn over your firearms. If that&#8217;s a problem and you wish to return to your country ‚Äì<br />
No. No problem.<br />
My men will escort you to your hotel.<br />
Liz: We&#8217;re being watched.<br />
Ressler: I didn&#8217;t notice him. I was too busy checking out Hugo Boss on the corner. Whoever he is, he isn&#8217;t a fed. That suit wasn&#8217;t bought on a government salary.<br />
[They enter restaurant]<br />
<b>Red:</b> The other one, the watercolorist, she ‚Äì legs like a shot-putter. She gets me in this headlock. I black out. Next thing I know, I wake up, no sheets, vaseline everywhere. The lipstick on the mirror overhead reads, &#8220;Same time next year?&#8221; I haven&#8217;t missed an art expo in Basel since. Lizzy! Please excuse me.<br />
Liz: What are you doing here?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I promised to help. I can&#8217;t be an effective resource if I&#8217;m thousands of miles from the action.<br />
Liz: It&#8217;s not safe. We just saw the CIA at the airport. They see you ‚Äì<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;ll be sure to say hello. Uzbekistan has no extradition treaty with the United States.<br />
Who are your friends over there?<br />
Go get cleaned up. We&#8217;ll have dinner. I know a wonderful little hole in the wall that&#8217;s actually in a hole in the wall.</p>
<p>[ Elevator bell dings ]<br />
Ressler: What&#8217;s going on with you and Reddington? You two have a little lovers&#8217; quarrel?<br />
Liz: I don&#8217;t trust him.<br />
Ressler: Reddington&#8217;s untrustworthy? Hmm.<br />
[ Elevator creaks, thuds ]<br />
Aah! Welcome to my country.<br />
Denisov: The FBI in Uzbekistan ‚Äì  for a year, I tried to get your attention. Now here you are because the only thing Americans understand is violence.<br />
Liz: If you know so much about Americans, you&#8217;d know that our government doesn&#8217;t pay ransoms to terrorists.<br />
Denisov: One man&#8217;s terrorist, another man&#8217;s freedom fighter. I don&#8217;t want your money ‚Äì  not for myself, anyway. As you can see, business is good. I took your Agent Burke for another reason completely.<br />
Burke ‚Äì  that&#8217;s his name?<br />
Denisov: Almost 25 years ago, my country sold an American company, Anneca Oil, the rights to build a pipeline through Tashkent to Andijan Region. The price was absurd. The Uzbek people received a fraction of the value. Corruption ‚Äì well, you know. These things happen, and I don&#8217;t care. But now, the pipeline is leaking.<br />
Leaking?<br />
Hundreds of villagers have been killed, hundreds more are sick, and the company does nothing. Our lawyers are no match for your wealthy attorneys. The American embassy looks away. The CIA is here, watching, doing nothing, reporting on any threats to your American interests.<br />
Mr. Denisov ‚Äì<br />
Denisov: I took one of theirs. A vice president of Anneca Oil. I tell him that there are chemicals in the water that we drink, that our children bathe in. But he says no. The company did tests. The water is safe. So I did a test of my own. I give him back to you now to show you my good faith so you can show the others the truth. The negotiations for your Agent Burke begin tomorrow.</p>
<p>Liz [on phone]: We saw hostages, at least four. I don&#8217;t think Agent Burke was one, but he&#8217;s probably there.<br />
We have got to find that compound.<br />
That won&#8217;t be easy. The local army can&#8217;t even find them.<br />
Well, we got your photo of the guy Denisov released ‚Äì the Anneca VP ‚Äì compared it to known company execs and got a match ‚Äì Jeffrey Hanover.<br />
How long ago was he taken?<br />
That&#8217;s the thing. I don&#8217;t know. From what I can tell, Anneca never reported him missing.<br />
You&#8217;re kidding.<br />
They tried to handle it privately. If that pipeline is leaking, the last thing they want is attention.<br />
Liz: Yeah, well, I&#8217;ll tell you one thing. Whatever it was eating at Hanover&#8217;s flesh, it wasn&#8217;t just water.</p>
<p>Female doctor: He should survive. His skin has been burned, corroded.<br />
Ressler: And the chemicals?<br />
Doctor: It&#8217;s certainly consistent with prolonged exposure to benzene and polycyclic hydrocarbons commonly associated with oil development.<br />
Thank you, Doctor.</p>
<p>Agent Ressler. Dean Walker, EVP at Anneca. Just wanted to say thanks for bringing Jeff home.<br />
It&#8217;s all part of the job.<br />
Walker: I just flew in. Company sent me straightaway.<br />
If there&#8217;s anything you need, I&#8217;m here to help.<br />
Yeah, I doubt that. We saw you this morning watching us at the airport. How long have you really been here?<br />
Three weeks. The company sent me to deal with Denisov, see if we could work something out.<br />
Privately? Jeff&#8217;s family wanted it that way. They were afraid if the FBI got involved ‚Äì<br />
Maybe you&#8217;re the ones who were afraid.<br />
Anneca&#8217;s got nothing to hide.<br />
This leak Denisov keeps talking about ‚Äì<br />
He the one responsible. It&#8217;s a scam. His men sabotage the pipeline and then demand a fortune because the locals are getting sick.</p>
<p>Kushan: So this is how you respect my operation? I told you, you have no authority here.<br />
Denisov contacted us.<br />
Commander, I know this is your case, but if Denisov wants to talk to the FBI ‚Äì<br />
Not an option.<br />
It&#8217;s an option if Denisov says it&#8217;s an option. He&#8217;s the one who&#8217;s holding an American hostage. Yes, a Frenchman, a German, and many others.<br />
I&#8217;m sorry. You can&#8217;t order us not to talk to him.<br />
I could arrest you and your partner for interfering in my investigation.<br />
Ressler: What investigation? You&#8217;ve been tracking this guy and his group for over a year. He&#8217;s still abducting innocent people, holding them for ransom ‚Äì<br />
You and your partner will remain at the Tashlan Hotel under military guard.<br />
If you try to leave, your stay in Uzbekistan will be a lot longer than you bargained for, hmm? </p>
<p><b>Red:</b> Well, you certainly make friends fast. [ Ice cube clinks ] Truth is, I&#8217;m impressed. Not with you ‚Äì  with Ruslan.He never really struck me as a man of the people.<br />
Ressler. The guy&#8217;s a psychopath. He&#8217;s in over his head. He doesn&#8217;t know anything about pipelines.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Agent Keen is late.<br />
Ressler: She&#8217;s having room service. What, are you in the doghouse?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Oh, that&#8217;s a shame. She&#8217;s gonna miss the most tantalizingly delicious khorem baklava.<br />
Ressler: Ruslan&#8217;s a criminal. Even if Anneca comes to the table, Denisov would have no idea what to ask for. The guy doesn&#8217;t even know enough to know what he wants. The lawyers would eat him for lunch.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You may be right. When&#8217;s the next sit-down?<br />
Ressler: Tomorrow morning.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Well, given your new entourage, I gather you may need my help to attend.<br />
Ressler: Actually, I think we&#8217;ve got that covered.</p>
<p>[ Elevator bell dings ] [ Elevator creaks, thuds ]<br />
Liz: Mr. Denisov, thank you for your willingness to talk to us. The Bureau spoke with Anneca Oil, and the good news is, they want to fix this.<br />
Denisov: That is good news. To be honest, I was a little worried. [ Parroting Donald talking to Red ] I mean, who am I? I&#8217;m just a criminal. I don&#8217;t even know enough to know what I want. I will not be negotiating this deal myself. I&#8217;ve decided to bring in a professional, someone to make sure that the company lawyers don&#8217;t eat me for lunch.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Mr. Denisov, it is my pleasure to be here.<br />
Denisov: Hello.<br />
<b>Red:</b> My name is Raymond Reddington. [ To Liz &amp; Ressler ] And you are? </p>
<p>Cooper: I&#8217;ve spoken to my agents. They assure me Agent Burke is alive.<br />
Wright: So, where are we?<br />
Cooper: My people are concerned. They were driven to a village less than 40 miles from the SRU compound. They saw the damage being done by the pipeline firsthand.<br />
Heyworth (CIA): Wait. Your people know where the compound is located?<br />
Cooper: They don&#8217;t know the exact location, but based on drive time and the terrain they encountered, we think the compound is somewhere near the southeast base of the Zarafshan Range.<br />
Heyworth: We can have a black-ops team on the ground tonight.<br />
Cooper: That would be a mistake. We don&#8217;t know with certainty if Agent Burke is even there.<br />
Heyworth: I&#8217;m willing to take that chance.<br />
Cooper: And destroy the trust they&#8217;re trying to build with Denisov as well as endanger the lives of those still on the ground?<br />
Wright: I agree. At this point, a raid is premature. Agent Cooper, I&#8217;m assuming your informant can be of assistance on this one?<br />
Cooper: From what I hear, he&#8217;s right at the center of this.<br />
Wright: Then we stay the course for now.</p>
<p><b>Red:</b> [ To Denisov ] I will see to it that every one of your interests and expectations are met or exceeded.</p>
<p>Liz: What the hell are you doing?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m sorry. It&#8217;s been a while since I&#8217;ve done one of these. Did I screw up already?<br />
Liz: You&#8217;re not really gonna negotiate for Denisov, are you? You&#8217;re the one who insisted that our interaction be strictly professional. You gave us this case to help us get the agent back, not represent the other side.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Agent Keen, in this world, there are no sides, only players.‚ô§<br />
Are we really supposed to sit here and hammer out a deal?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Absolutely not. I was thinking we might get out for a bit. The first day of negotiation is rather like the first day of school.<br />
Get out? Where?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Let&#8217;s go on a field trip, shall we? [ Goat bleats ] </p>
<p>Denisov: What you&#8217;re smelling is benzene, a common pollutant in oil production. It&#8217;s in the air we breathe and the food we eat. This way. We boil all our water for drinking and add andrographis to counteract the toxins.<br />
Does that work?<br />
No. Carcinogens are ingested and cause melanomas, damage internal organs&#8211; lung, liver, and kidney failure.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Somewhere, 6,000 miles away, a group of bean counters in a boardroom did a cost-benefit analysis and concluded that these people aren&#8217;t worth the cost of responsibly maintaining their pipeline.‚ô§<br />
Ressler: The exec I talked to, he said your men were sabotaging the pipeline. Said it was a scam.<br />
Denison: My youngest brother died of benzene poisoning last year.<br />
<b>Red:</b> So, who&#8217;s the hostage here, Agent Burke or these poor devils?<br />
Ressler: Look, I don&#8217;t care what math they did. No company can ignore this. It&#8217;s bad for business.<br />
Liz: Only if someone can prove the truth. Anneca spends a fortune on lobbyists to make sure that doesn&#8217;t happen. Maybe we can contact the State Department, see if they can apply some pressure, try and clean up this mess.<br />
<b>Red:</b> And I can see to it that Agent Burke is released unharmed. See? No sides. Only players.</p>
<p>[ Cellphone rings ]<br />
Keen.<br />
Wilcox: Agent Keen. I&#8217;m glad I caught you. You know, you&#8217;re not an easy woman to reach.<br />
Liz: I&#8217;m sorry. Who is this?<br />
Detective Martin Wilcox, Metro PD. Assistant Director Cooper&#8217;s office gave me your number. I hope I caught you at an okay time.<br />
What&#8217;s up, Detective?<br />
I&#8217;m looking into this missing-persons case. The vic actually works for the PD. It&#8217;s a Lieutenant Ames, DC harbormaster.<br />
How can I help?<br />
I heard that you two ran into each other up on one of the harbor rigs. It looks like you gave him one of your business cards.<br />
Right.<br />
Wilcox: Right. I think you said something about the FBI searching for fugitives out of Cumberland. Thing is, I-I&#8217;ve made a few calls, and nobody seems to know anything about it.<br />
Well, that&#8217;s because it didn&#8217;t happen. It was a cover. I couldn&#8217;t share why with the Lieutenant at the time.<br />
Is there any chance you can share it with me now? Might help me clear this case.<br />
I&#8217;m sorry.<br />
Wilcox: Well, you&#8217;re gonna have to tell me something. I mean, you being out there alone, drawing your weapon, giving a false story ‚Äì it raises some questions.<br />
Liz: I&#8217;ve already said more than I can say. May I ask ‚Äì Lieutenant Ames ‚Äì  who reported him missing?<br />
His wife. Married 32 years. :-(<br />
Oh. Well, I hope you find him, Detective. Good luck.</p>
<p>[ Uzbek folk music plays ]<br />
Liz: You told Ruslan the State Department was open to the idea of an inquiry.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You haven&#8217;t touched your baklava.<br />
Liz: You told him, and he&#8217;s not interested?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Just one bite.<br />
Liz: I didn&#8217;t come here for the baklava. I came here to talk about the negotiation.<br />
[ Tango music plays ] [ Applause ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Ah. A Russian milonga. Watch closely, Lizzy. Everything you need to know about negotiation is there in the tango milonga.‚ô§</p>

<h3>Script 2:12 The Kenyon Family</h3>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<i><b>Blurb:</b> A religious survivalist sect which favors child marriage and polygamy, stores contraband on its grounds for criminals. Red follows up on the instructions Alan Fitch gave him to find a safe in St Peterburg. Red buys Liz an apartment.</i></p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Kenyon: &#8220;Since Lot was afraid to stay in Zoar, he and his two daughters settled in the hill country, where he lived in a cave. The firstborn said to the younger &#8216;Our father is getting old, and there is not a man in the land to have intercourse with us as is the custom everywhere. Come. Let us ply our father with wine and then lie with him, that we may ensure posterity by our father.<br />
&#8216;So that night, they plied their father with wine.&#8221; And the firstborn went in and lay with her father.<br />
[ Insects chirping ]<br />
Kenyon: &#8220;The next day, the firstborn said to the younger, &#8216;Let us ply him with wine again tonight. And then you go in and lie with him.&#8217; So that night, too, they plied their father with wine. And then the younger one went in and lay with her father. And so it was that the two daughters of Lot became pregnant by their father.  And thus, Lord, we maketh your word our command!&#8221;</p>
<blockquote><p>
All: <i>‚ô´ Amen! down to the river to pray<br />
studying about that good old way<br />
and who shall wear that starry crown good Lord,<br />
show me the way oh, sisters,<br />
let&#8217;s go down let&#8217;s go down come on down<br />
oh, sisters, let&#8217;s go down down to the river to pray<br />
as I went down in the river to pray ‚Ä¶ &#8220;</i>
</p></blockquote>
<p>Woman: Dearly beloved, we are gathered here in the sight of God and in the face of this family to join together this ‚Äì<br />
[ Woman gasps, people murmuring ] [ Glass breaking ] [ Women screaming ] [ Screaming intensifies ] </p>
<p>Cooper: What do you feel like ‚Äì Italian, Thai?<br />
Charlene: Are we really gonna do this?<br />
Cooper: Do what? I&#8217;m hungry.<br />
Charlene: Not talk about it.<br />
Cooper: I&#8217;ll probably get turned down. The trial ‚Äì nobody gets in this thing. It&#8217;s false hope.<br />
Charlene: Did you hear what the doctor said? I mean, were you even listening? I mean, he said the prognosis is ‚Äì<br />
Cooper: He said he couldn&#8217;t predict.<br />
Charlene: No, he said that the trial was your best shot. You don&#8217;t want to do it, fine. Then do it for me. I can live with that.<br />
Cooper: Just want to think about it.<br />
Charlene: There&#8217;s nothing to think about. I don&#8217;t care if you get fat. I don&#8217;t care if you lose your hair. You&#8217;re applying for this trial. You&#8217;re gonna be accepted. Do you understand me? I am not losing you.<br />
Cooper: Soon as I get to the office I&#8217;ll make the call.</p>
<p>Liz: DMV? Really? I&#8217;ve never even seen you drive.<br />
<b>Red:</b> That little fella, the one through the glass, his name is Glen Carter. His mother calls him &#8220;Jelly Bean.&#8221; A loathsome individual who, sad to say, possesses an uncanny ability to locate anything.<br />
Woman behind him: Achoo! [ Coughs ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ Sighs ] I presume you&#8217;ve heard of Justin Kenyon?<br />
Liz: The smiling public face of the militia movement. Who hasn&#8217;t? Yes.<br />
<b>Red:</b> The very voice of reason, the rebel darling of the fringe right ‚Äì charming, rustic, camera-ready, the perfect spokesman to spin vile hatred and prejudice into treacly dross that passes for plainspoken common sense.<br />
Liz: Forget it.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Excuse me?<br />
Liz: Justice knows exactly who Justin Kenyon is. We know what he is. The Church of the Shield is a cesspool of polygamy, doomsday paranoia, ritualized elder and child abuse, but he also has four of the most prominent civil rights attorneys in the country on retainer ‚Äì we can&#8217;t touch him.<br />
<b>Red:</b> How do you suppose he pays for those high-priced lawyers ‚Äì charitable contributions?<br />
Liz: His church has been audited by the IRS every year for the past decade. His books are impeccable.<br />
<b>Red:</b> So are mine.</p>
<p>Liz: Justin Kenyon ‚Äì head of the Church of the Shield, a polygamist cult located on a 15,000-acre reserve in the Smoky Mountains.<br />
Aram: Kenyon declared it a nation-state and petitioned to secede in US District Court three decades ago.<br />
Liz: According to Reddington, Kenyon has dozens of shipping containers buried on his property. Terrorists, cartels, and criminals contract with him to store cargo, no questions asked. Reddington compiled a partial inventory from his sources. It includes all manner of contraband, from drugs and hot merchandise to military ordnance, antiaircraft guns, missiles, RPGs, Semtex.<br />
Ressler: Sounds like a one-stop storage facility for the criminal underworld.<br />
Liz: In 1982, Kenyon published a book entitled &#8220;The Silver Bear Prophecies,&#8221; which he purported were delivered to him by the spirit of an ancient Druid elder. In it, he claims to be the latter-day incarnation of an entity the Silver Bear called &#8220;The Ken&#8217;yon.&#8221;<br />
Samar Navabi: How convenient.<br />
Liz: Ken&#8217;yon and his followers will ascend into Heaven for six days and return to ‚Äì and I quote ‚Äì &#8220;Rain fire upon the New Babylon, the defiled States of America, and our children shall cleanse<br />
her streets with the blood of her founder&#8217;s enemies.&#8221; According to Reddington, Ken&#8217;yon has fallen off the radar. David: What do you know?<br />

David: You&#8217;re right. I am.<br />
[Shouts] Coward! [ Gunfire; David is killed ] </p>
<p>Liz: ATF&#8217;s been over the grounds. They&#8217;ve searched the buried containers. If you&#8217;re wondering about what you stored there, it&#8217;s long gone. [ Drawer closes ] What&#8217;s this?<br />
<b>Red:</b> A key. I bought you an apartment at the Audrey, top floor, splendid view of the Potomac.<br />
Liz: Why?<br />
<b>Red:</b> It&#8217;s time to leave the motel behind.<br />
Liz: [ Sighs ] I&#8217;m happy where I am. Thank you.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You&#8217;ve been many things lately, Lizzy, but happy is not one of them.‚ô§ That motor lodge you call home crushes the spirit, smothers the soul.‚ô§<br />

<b>Red:</b> I once stayed at a villa in Bali with a view of the Indian Ocean. Every morning, all I saw before me was possibility. That and a gorgeous housekeeper named Putu, who used to ‚Äì<br />
Liz: Thanks, but, no, thanks. I wish you&#8217;d stop.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Stop what?<br />
Liz: Trying. Stop hoping things are gonna get better between us. You and me, it&#8217;s just business. That&#8217;s all it&#8217;s ever gonna be.‚ô§</p>
<p>[ Crickets chirping ] [ <b>Red</b> and Dembe arrive at the Kenyon compound. Red enters the church, now abandoned, tips over pulpit and opens a trap door. It&#8217;s a black limo, flying two flags one on either side of the hood: one, the U.S. flag, the other the flag of the President of the United States. <h3>Script 2:13 The Deer Hunter</h3>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<i><b>Blurb:</b> A serial killer appears be a man ‚Äì and a woman. Red tries to reach the man whose number was in the safe in St Petersburg. Red scolds Liz for taking too many risks. She tell him she has the Fulcrum. Aram worries about his hair. </i></p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Voiceover: Previously on The Blacklist ‚Ä¶<br />
Aleko: I went out for a smoke and he was here.<br />
Liz: What the hell?<br />
Tom: You let this guy go, he&#8217;s going to the cops. We are all going to jail, starting with you.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Telephone rings ] Keen.<br />
Detective Martin Wilcox, Metro PD. I&#8217;m looking into this missing-persons case. Lieutenant Ames, DC Harbormaster.<br />
Liz: I had no idea Tom would kill him.<br />
Ressler: What about witnesses?<br />
Wilcox: Just want to ask you a few questions, then you&#8217;re free to go. You are Samuel Aleko. I know you were there.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Liz: My father was killed because of the Fulcrum, because you and your people came for it that night. ‚Ä¶ This charade of you pretending to care about me was a waste of your time because I don&#8217;t know where it is.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Fitch: I have a safe. It&#8217;s in St. Petersburg.<br />
Dembe: The number from the safe traces to a blind exchange. We can&#8217;t identify the party you&#8217;ll be speaking to.<br />
<b>Red</b> (on phone): Who the hell is this? </p>
<p>[ Siren wailing in distance ]<br />
Liz [to class in auditorium]: Our suspect is patient, calm. He likely spends hours scouting the prey. He&#8217;s only interested in big men, the ones who are hard to take down, like the big bucks in the wild. Now, you&#8217;re looking for an incredibly smart offender, highly organized. White male, likely 35 to 40. It is the sport that he&#8217;s seduced by, the ritual of the hunt.  When he does finally make his move, it happens fast, striking in a blitz-style attack most never see coming. His heart-shot prey rarely make it over 100 feet before bleeding out. ‚Äì That moment is everything to him ‚Äì  the rush of control.</p>
<p>The typical mutilation killer focuses on a specific area of the anatomy that suits their interest ‚Äì the face, the eyes or mouth, the extremities, hands, breasts, genitalia. But this one&#8217;s different&#8211; he&#8217;s interested in total domination of the body. He guts them, removing the organs with surgical precision, but then leaving them in a pile.</p>
<p>But these aren&#8217;t sex crimes, which indicates they are instead crimes of domination, an effort on his part to gain control over men who, based on their physical similarities, represent a man who once had dominance over him ‚Äì a father, an older brother. It is my belief that &#8220;The Deer Hunter&#8221; is, in fact, a very slight, rather weak man.</p>
<p>Yes ‚Äì blue shirt.</p>
<p>Man in audience: They say he takes a souvenir.<br />
Liz: It&#8217;s not a souvenir, it&#8217;s a final act of domination. While his prey&#8217;s body is still warm, he carves out the liver and takes a single ceremonial bite.</p>
<p>Aleko: Man, we had a deal. I testify against Keen and her husband, I tell you how they killed the harbormaster, and I walk.<br />
Wilcox: Yeah, you will walk, when the trial&#8217;s over. Until then, you&#8217;re being charged as an accessory.<br />
Aleko: I told you everything.<br />
Wilcox: Yeah. And because of that, you&#8217;re gonna be the star witness in the murder trial of FBI Agent Elizabeth Keen. You&#8217;re gonna testify in open court. You&#8217;re gonna testify before the grand jury. You&#8217;re gonna be deposed until you&#8217;re blue in the face. And if you change your story by so much as a comma, your immunity deal will be voided and you&#8217;re gonna go to prison for the rest of your life. Am I clear?<br />
Aleko: Yeah.</p>
<p>[ Public telephone rings ]<br />
<b>Red</b>: Yes?<br />
Man: Sorry I cut our previous call short. I was not confident the line was secure.<br />
<b>Red</b>: Tell me your name.<br />
Man: Not yet.<br />
<b>Red</b>: Then you have me at a disadvantage.<br />
Man: Yes.<br />
<b>Red</b>: Alan Fitch directed me to that safe. Your number was inside. He wanted us to talk. Why? What does he want me to know?<br />
Man: <b><i>It is happening.</b></i>‚ô§<br />
<b>Red</b>: What is? What&#8217;s happening?<br />
Man: No, not like this ‚Äì in person. Broadway and 92nd.Center island, south side.<br />
[ Receiver clicks ] </p>
<p><b>Red</b>: A graduate seminar. Was there a slide show? ‚ãò‚ãô We need to talk about the Fulcrum.<br />
Liz: I told you, I don&#8217;t know anything about it.<br />
<b>Red</b>: Elizabeth, one of the reasons I&#8217;m still alive is due to my love of reading, whether it be words on a page that reveal the author&#8217;s thoughts, emotions, imagination, or whether it be people in conversation, ‚Äì to ignore what they say and instead read their expression, posture, their gestures. Lizzy, you&#8217;re lying.‚ô§<br />
Liz: I&#8217;m not.<br />
<b>Red</b>: What if we made a deal? I help you find your serial killer, and you tell me about the Fulcrum.<br />
Liz: You&#8217;re not even interested in serial killers.<br />
<b>Red</b>: True. I find them unimaginative and woefully predictable. But I am interested in the cases that you and the FBI have wrong.<br />
Liz: Wrong?<br />
<b>Red</b>: The most critical assumption you&#8217;re making about The Deer Hunter is wrong. Do we have a deal or not? </p>
<p><b>Red</b> [at FBI]: This brute they call The Deer Hunter isn&#8217;t a buck at all, but instead a delicate doe.<br />
Liz: A woman? I disagree with you.<br />
<b>Red</b>: Okay. But your killer attacks from a distance, indicating the predator&#8217;s smaller, perhaps unable to overpower their prey. Men tend to kill in close proximity ‚Äì strangulation, blunt instrument, a knife. By contrast, women tend to favor weapons that can be used from further away ‚Äì poison, a gun, a crossbow.<br />
Liz: Richard Kuklinski was 6&#8217;5&#8243;, 300 pounds, and one of his favorite weapons of choice was cyanide.<br />
<b>Red</b>: Yes, but male <i>serial</i> killers are predominantly, overwhelmingly sexually sadistic. In this case, there is not the slightest indication of a sexual motive.<br />
Liz: Aileen Wuornos was a prostitute who lured her victims in with the promise of sex.<br />
<b>Red</b>: The Deer Hunter has been active for over a decade, from the truck driver in Des Moines in 2003 to the doorman in Adams Morgan last night. That&#8217;s 12 years. The average length of a killing spree for a man is two, perhaps three. Yes, Agent Keen, for every rule there is an exception. Each factor, taken separately, is not conclusive, but put them together and it&#8217;s clear ‚Äì you haven&#8217;t found your man because he&#8217;s a woman.</p>
<p>Aram: Uh, Agent Keen, uh, the ME called. He just finished his autopsy on the latest victim.<br />
<b>Red</b> [tossling Aram&#8217;s hair as he passes by]: I used to have a teeming mane just like that.<br />
Aram: Oh. Uh ‚Äì Thank you.</p>
<p>Ryerson [Medical Examiner]: Every kill is identical. Same clean incisions at the stomach and the liver, same knots binding the anus.<br />
Ressler: No variations?<br />
Ryerson: When field dressing&#8217;s done well, it&#8217;s like an autopsy. The way he opens subjects, I want to show you‚Äì<br />
Liz: What is it?<br />
Ryerson: I left that body covered.<br />
Ressler: The hallway.<br />

Kruse: Okay, okay, okay!<br />
Ressler: Don&#8217;t move!<br />
Kruse: It&#8217;s just my phone!<br />
Liz or Ressler: Hands!<br />
Kruse: Okay. It&#8217;s just my phone, okay? </p>
<p><i>‚ô´  say nighty-night and kiss me [ Sighs ] just hold me tight and tell me you&#8217;ll miss me while I&#8217;m alone and blue as can be </i></p>
<p>Tracy [to her pet canary]: Stop looking at me like that. I&#8217;m fine. I&#8217;ll be fine. It&#8217;s not ‚Äì I don&#8217;t like it any more than you do. ‚Ä¶ But someone has to do this! ‚Ä¶ This is Chad Henning. ‚Ä¶ Mommy has to go across town to see him. [Sniffles] To see Chad Henning. I won&#8217;t be long.</p>
<p>Ressler: What the hell were you doing in the ME&#8217;s office?<br />

Ressler: There&#8217;s no research in that rag sheet. It&#8217;s gossip and innuendo. So, what were you really doing there? You used fake credentials to get into the ME&#8217;s office.<br />

Kruse: The first six victims, Mark Rodgers through Perry Holloman, he was experimenting. The field dressing became cleaner, he switched from a folder to a field blade<br />

Liz or Ressler: Are you saying he didn&#8217;t?<br />

Liz or Ressler: You think we&#8217;re dealing with a copycat.<br />
Kruse: The Deer Hunter is an artist. The guy you&#8217;re looking for is a forger.</p>
<p>[ Cellphone buzzes ]<br />
Liz: Keen.<br />

Wilcox: That&#8217;s not gonna fly anymore. See, the thing is, recovering the body is not the only development in the case. I also found Samuel Aleko. He places you at the scene, Agent Keen ‚Äì you and your ex-husband. He tells quite a story. Says the two of you are stone-cold killers.<br />
Liz: Even if I wanted to answer your questions, before I could talk, you would need to get ‚Äì A federal judge to rule that my investigation supercedes your case.<br />
Wilcox: It&#8217;s ‚Äì it&#8217;s in the works. An AUSA&#8217;s gonna sit down with Mr.  Aleko, hear what he has to say. And I-I have no doubt that, as a result of that conversation, a petition&#8217;s gonna be filed in federal court requesting that I have complete access to any of your allegedly classified information.<br />

<p>[ Car door closes ] [ Sighs ] [ Telephone rings ]<br />
Ressler: I&#8217;ve been through every case file, and I&#8217;ll be damned if Kruse doesn&#8217;t have a point. I mean, the last six kills are identical.<br />

Tom may have killed this guy, but &#8220;FBI Agent Goes To Prison&#8221; is the headline. All they&#8217;re gonna care about is taking a bite out of y‚Äì  That&#8217;s it!<br />

Ressler: Kruse was right about the copycat. I can prove it.</p>
<p>[ Door closes ]<br />
Mary: I&#8217;m sorry. I don&#8217;t mean to second-guess you.<br />

Mary: It&#8217;s just ‚Äì my son. If anything were to happen to me‚Äì<br />

<h3>Script 2:14 T Earl King VI</h3>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<i><b>Blurb:</b> Red becomes the special guest of an eccentric billionaire family that makes its money holding underground auctions of exotic merchandise for those willing to pay.</i></p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Francis: Ah, good evening, father. You&#8217;re looking sharp.<br />
Earl (Father): [ Voice box ] Mr. Valmont, the tally.<br />
Valmont: Moments away. Gentlemen. [ Clock ticking ] [ Clock chiming ]<br />
Earl: What are the standing totals?<br />
Valmont: Master Tyler King, $67,800,000. All bids paid in full. Master Francis King, $67,400,000 with one account pending for $1.8 million.<br />
Francis: You haven&#8217;t won yet.<br />
Tyler: I have, and you know it.<br />
Valmont: The contractual deadline has passed. The last tally stands. Mr. Cardini failed to wire funds for his lot. I&#8217;m sorry.<br />
Earl: Well, boys, get on with it.<br />
[ Francis hold pistol to head, pulls trigger. Gun clicks. It&#8217;s Russian roulette! ]<br />
Tyler: Next time.</p>
<p>Handler: I&#8217;m sorry. I&#8217;ve got nothing right for you.<br />
Tom: If something comes in‚Äì I just need to go back in, okay? I don&#8217;t care what it is. I&#8217;ll take anything.<br />
Handler: You don&#8217;t want to do that. Sit down. [ Sighs ] You got class. You&#8217;re the boyfriend. You&#8217;re the hip, young executive. That&#8217;s where the top dollar is. Anything else, for you, is a sinful waste.<br />
Tom: But I don&#8217;t care. I don&#8217;t care about top dollar. I just need to go back under. Bud, please.<br />
It&#8217;s me. I can play anything.<br />
Handler: Don&#8217;t tell me that girl got to you. If you need a palate-cleansing so bad, I may have something. How&#8217;s your German? </p>
<p>[ Knock on door ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> I hope you&#8217;re considering the apartment at the Audrey. You must stop living like this.<br />
Liz: By all means, come right in. Make yourself at home.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Madeline Pratt has been abducted.<br />
Liz: What do you care? She almost got us both killed.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Foreplay. ‚ãò‚ãô My relationship with Madeline is nuanced. Confounding, yet captivating, she&#8217;s a singular woman, and the world is far more interesting with her in it. What&#8217;s more, her abductors meet every requisite that defines inclusion on the Blacklist. The Kings.<br />
Liz: The kings? Of what?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Not &#8220;king&#8221; as in &#8220;king and castle.&#8221; Earl King and his two sons, Tyler and Francis, descendents of a Senescent Dynasty. Their forefathers built a fortune on the backs of British undesirables, forcing them into decades of indentured servitude‚Äì  a tradition that has been passed from generation to generation that still continues today.<br />
Liz: So, what does this have to do with Madeline Pratt?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Madeline has made a number of well-heeled enemies over the years, many of whom would pay a handsome price for her head. If merely saving a woman&#8217;s life isn&#8217;t enough to warrant the Bureau&#8217;s interest, consider what taking down a dynasty like the King family would mean. Every transaction meticulously recorded for posterity in the family ledger. Sometimes, years pass between auctions. They&#8217;re never held in the same place twice. The guest lists are constantly changing. This is your chance to solve a century and a half&#8217;s worth of abductions and thefts from the Davidoff Morini Stradivarius to the disappearance of Raoul Wallenberg. This phone belonged to a boy in the port of Lisbon, where Madeline was abducted.<br />
Liz: Pictures of the kidnapping.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Find the jackals who took Madeline and they&#8217;ll inevitably lead you to the Kings.</p>
<p>Ressler: So, we&#8217;re going after one blacklister to save another. Tell me how that makes sense.<br />
Liz: Earl King and his two sons, Tyler and Francis ‚Äì  from available intel, they appear to be an eccentric family of trust-fund billionaires. According to Reddington, they supplement their family fortune with profits from their illegal auctions. Six months ago, seized by MI5 disappeared from their evidence vault in Leeds. The painting ‚Äì stolen from the Van Gogh Museum in Amsterdam. Reddington claims both these items will fall under the gavel at the Kings&#8217; next auction.</p>
<p>Aram: I think I might have something. I isolated this image from the pics, ran it against our known-tattoo database, and got a hit. Silvio Haratz, a Brazilian-born kidnapper working the world&#8217;s K&amp;R hotspots. If the auction&#8217;s gonna be held on US soil, Haratz is headed here.<br />
Ressler: We&#8217;re gonna need local intel.<br />
Aram: The DOJ has an active file on Haratz, but it&#8217;s restricted access. I can&#8217;t open it without throwing up red flags in the Attorney General&#8217;s office.<br />
Cooper. I may know someone who can help. The rest of you, dig up anything you can on the Kings.</p>
<p>[ Telephone ringing ]<br />
Cooper: What do you have on Haratz?<br />
Tom Connolly [AG]: Enough to haul him in, but not enough to make it stick. That&#8217;s all I can say. We&#8217;re building a case. ‚ãò‚ãô I have a good friend, CEO of a med-tech company. Got himself mixed up in a fraud scheme. The grand jury convened, and it&#8217;s looking like there&#8217;s going to be an indictment. They&#8217;ll seize his assets. It would be nice if he had a chance to shield a little something in a blind trust for his kids.<br />
Cooper: You want me to tip him off?<br />
Tom: He&#8217;s a good friend, close friend. And I take care of my friends. ‚ãò‚ãô How&#8217;s that clinical trial? The one I got you into? You look well.</p>
<p>[ Cellphone rings ]<br />
Liz:  Agent Keen.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Hello.<br />
Liz: The suspect&#8217;s name is Silvio Haratz. He&#8217;s using a safe house called The Palace. We&#8217;re on our way.<br />
<b>Red:</b> No. I know The Palace, You people get within a mile of that place, he&#8217;ll be made. I&#8217;ll handle it.<br />
Liz: Forget it, Reddington. We&#8217;re not on your payroll, and you can&#8217;t call us off. We&#8217;re on it.</p>
<p>[ Red and Dembe are going through darkened rooms at hotel, guns drawn. Others, including many with guns, enter. Madeline Pratt and Francis are among them. ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> How much do you want for her?<br />
Francis: You can have her.<br />
[ Electricity crackles ]<br />
Madeline: Sorry, Dembe. [ She tases him ]<br />
[ Body thuds ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Well-played, Madeline. Payback for my little gambit last year, I presume.<br />
Maddie: Consider us even.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Francis: Raymond &#8220;Red&#8221; Reddington. Lot number 11. [ Chuckles ] Beautiful.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Careful there, boys. You don&#8217;t want to bruise the merchandise.‚ô§</p>
<p>[ Door opens ] [ Camera shutter clicks ]<br />
Ressler: We intercepted Dembe.<br />
Liz: He informed us they used Pratt as bait, faked the kidnapping in order to bring Red into the Kings&#8217; custody.<br />
Samar: King family auctions are all about providing criminals with items of value. What&#8217;s more valuable than Reddington?<br />
Cooper: Where are we on potential auction locations?<br />
Aram: The Kings have real-estate holdings all over the world. You&#8217;d have to be invited to know where this thing is.<br />
Liz: Let&#8217;s not focus on the Kings. Let&#8217;s focus on the Kings&#8217; guests. Try and match the items we know they have for sale with the people who might be interested in buying them.<br />
Cooper: We&#8217;ll put together a list. Alert Immigration and the TSA on major points of entry.<br />
Identify and report only. Do not detain.</p>
<p><b>Red:</b> Your insistence on not speaking, sir, is making a tedious exercise ever so much worse.<br />
Tyler: Over here, gentlemen.<br />
Boy in cage: Please. Someone help me.<br />
Tyler: Raymond Reddington in the flesh.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You must be Tyler. I hope you&#8217;re not as short-sighted as your brother. I could be one of your most valued customers.<br />
Tyler: As I recall, you&#8217;re one of the few prospects who rejected an invitation to our auction. Nice try, though.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I haven&#8217;t even begun to try. There is one thing about your family that&#8217;s always intrigued me. Statistically, [ Added: 65% of family fortunes] are frittered away by the second generation. [ Added: By the third generation, it&#8217;s 90%]. How is it that the Kings have successfully defied that trend? You must tell me your secret.‚ô§<br />
Tyler: Winner takes all.<br />
<b>Red:</b> And the loser?<br />
Tyler: None of your business.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ To tailor ] Really, I&#8217;m all for being thorough, but at this point, you&#8217;re just taking the nickel tour.</p>
<p>[ Keyboard clacking ]<br />
Liz: Alexi Koskov, a Russian oligarch with an extensive collection of stolen masterpieces. The Art Crime Division says he&#8217;s been trying to acquire the Van Gogh since it disappeared in 2002. Samar: Koskov&#8217;s on the no-fly list. How can he get into the country?<br />
Aram: He can&#8217;t. But his new acquisitions emissary, Josephine Sullivan, flew in from LA this morning. She just checked in to The Vanguard.<br />
Cooper: Bring her in.</p>
<p>Francis: I presume you&#8217;ve been downstairs.<br />
Tyler: I have.<br />
Francis: Reddington&#8217;s a game changer. You can&#8217;t win.<br />
Tyler: I have no intention of quitting now. Even if you win, I only have a 16% chance of losing&#8211; one in six.</p>
<p>Samar: We know you&#8217;re working as a representative for Alexi Koskov to authenticate and purchase a stolen painting from an illegal auction. As such, we can charge you as an accessory after the fact, not only for the Van Gogh, but for every crime the King family has committed to acquire the rest of their stock, including kidnapping and false imprisonment.<br />
Liz: This is the Bureau&#8217;s file on you and your boss.<br />
[ Papers thud ]<br />
Liz: Koskov is untouchable. But you&#8217;re right here.</p>
<p>Samar: Her instructions were to introduce herself to the concierge at The Harleston Read Hotel. Owned by the King family trust.<br />
Liz: Everyone there is on their payroll.<br />
Cooper: That&#8217;s it?<br />

<p>[ Cellphone vibrates ]<br />
Liz: Keen.<br />

<p>[ Red is being given a shave ] [ Wheelchair motor whirring ]<br />

You hear that? That&#8217;s the market telling me you are in demand. What kind of a commodity are you? A wealth of secrets and information? Or are you an impulse purchase for a buyer to settle a score? You scare people, Red. How much would you pay to be rid of your deepest fear?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;ve always found fear to be my most valuable sense.‚ô§ But then again, you Kings demonstrate a propensity for having more dollars than sense. [ Chuckles ] Your son Tyler was telling me‚Äì &#8220;Winner takes all,&#8221; I believe he said. I&#8217;m curious strictly from an estate-planning perspective. What exactly does that mean?<br />

<h3>Script 2:15 The Major</h3>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<i><b>Blurb:</b> Red wants compensation from The Major, the man who provided Tom for him to keep an eye on Liz ‚Äì but not to get involved. Liz testifies in chambers about the Harbormaster&#8217;s murder. Dembe cautions Red that it&#8217;s time to tell Liz.</i></p>

Man: Hey! Stop! Somebody stop that kid! Hey, get back here!<br />
[ Tires screech ]<br />

Jake/Tom.d That&#8217;s not what social services says.<br />

<p>[ Elevator bell dings ]<br />

‚ãò‚ãô<br />

Denner: Really? Well, here&#8217;s what I don&#8217;t appreciate, counsel. I don&#8217;t appreciate being instructed as to what will or will not happen in my courtroom.<br />

Wright: No, they don&#8217;t.<br />

And we shouldn&#8217;t have to take the government&#8217;s word for the fact that national security might be involved. It&#8217;s our call to make. We&#8217;re not asking for a second opinion. Markin: Marty.<br />
[ Gavel bangs ]<br />

Wright: And we agree.<br />
Denny: That call should not be made by the people or Detective Wilcox or even a grand jury.<br />
Wright: Thank you, Your Honor.<br />

<p>[ Door opens ]<br />

[Flashback: ] [ Helicopter blades whirring ] [ Sirens wail ] [ End Flashback ]<br />

[ Flashback: ] <b>Red:</b> Agent Keen, what a pleasure. [ End Flashback ]<br />

Assistant: Got it.<br />

Assistant: Yes, sir.</p>
<p><i>[ ‚ô´ German metal music playing ]</i> [ Tom&#8217;s target approaches him for gun sales ]</p>
<p><b>Red:</b> Well, that went as well as could be expected. We got a lead on Keen and an invitation to sit in the Minister&#8217;s box at next year&#8217;s Slasher Cup. Cultural peculiarities notwithstanding, I find cockfighting to be abominable. However, truth be told, I do love fried chicken.<br />

<p>Wilcox: Sorry to interrupt, Your Honor. This couldn&#8217;t wait.<br />
Judge Denner: What am I looking at?<br />

Trace amounts of Samuel Aleko&#8217;s blood were found on the casing.<br />

Wilcox: Five hours ago. Your Honor, this is ‚Äì This is direct physical evidence that Agent Keen lied to the court. She says that she never saw Mr. Aleko on that ship, but that can&#8217;t be reconciled with the fact that a bullet fired from her gun passed through Mr. Aleko&#8217;s body and was found on the ship with his blood on it. It&#8217;s proof that she&#8217;s trying to cover up the truth, Your Honor, and the truth is that Elizabeth Keen killed Eugene Ames.</p>

<h3>Script 2:16 Tom Keen</h3>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<i><b>Blurb:</b> Liz is in court to learn if she will go to trial for the murder of the Harbormaster when an unexpected witness appears. Liz sells the apartment Red gave her in the Audrey Hotel. Cooper meets with Tom Connolly. </i></p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<b><i>Previously on The Blacklist ‚Ä¶</i></b><br />
Denner: You said that you were on official business when you encountered Mr. Ames on the ship the Phoenix.<br />

<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m glad we had this talk. I know you&#8217;ll do the right thing.<br />

I am not going down. Not for her. And sure as hell not for you.</p>
<p>Liz: Any word?<br />
Charlene: You really don&#8217;t have to stay.<br />
Liz: Well Charlene, the last thing I want to do is pry, but Dr. Harper mentioned his &#8220;condition.&#8221; Charlene: Harold&#8217;s a private man. ‚Ä¶ Harold has a brain tumor. Glioblastoma, it&#8217;s called. Doctors found it last year when he was admitted after being attacked. They suggested that he leave the Bureau. Any undue stress could exacerbate his illness. But ‚Äì but Harold, that&#8211; that job It means everything to him.<br />
Liz: I&#8217;m so sorry. I had no idea.<br />
Charlene: The original prognosis was less than a year. But we found this experimental trial program. By some miracle, Harold was accepted. They were giving him some new chemotherapy drug. [ Sighs ] We thought it might be working, but after today I&#8217;m not so sure. Liz, you can&#8217;t say anything. Please promise me. Harold is so proud, the idea that [Chuckles] you and the others feeling sorry for him ‚Äì<br />
Liz: No, I understand. This stays between us. You have my word.<br />
Charlene: Thank you.</p>
<p>Aram: I&#8217;m collecting signatures for a get-well card for Mr. Cooper.<br />
Samar: &#8220;Get well, bitch. We&#8217;ve got some partying to do&#8221;?<br />
Aram: Too much? I just thought ‚Äì I mean, I wanted to make him laugh, you know? I mean, if it&#8217;s serious.<br />

Aram: Wow. Guess I don&#8217;t need the card anymore.</p>
<p>Did you find Tom?<br />
Ressler: Yeah, we found him. Told him what was at stake. He wasn&#8217;t moved.<br />
Samar: Didn&#8217;t realize you were interested in his opinion.<br />

[ Keys thud, drawer closes ]<br />

<p>Court officer: All rise.<br />
Judge Denner: I will make this quick. This whole business started because the Justice Department sought to quash a lawful subpoena issued to Harold Cooper, Assistant FBI Director.<br />
Ms. Wright?<br />
Wright: Mr. Cooper had a medical issue, Your Honor. He&#8217;s unable to be with us.<br />

Wright: On behalf of the Attorney General himself, I must insist.<br />

Wright: I&#8217;m asking the court to withhold any ruling until the AG&#8217;s rep has been afforded ‚Äì<br />

Court officer: Your Honor.<br />
Denner: What is it?<br />
CO: We have a situation in the corridor.<br />

Tom: Yes.<br />
Denner: And you are?<br />
Tom: My name is Tom Keen.<br />

Tom: She saved me.<br />
Denner: She held you captive on the boat the Phoenix to squeeze you for intelligence about your employer.<br />
Tom: Yeah, look. None of that matters. All right, the only thing that matters is that I killed that man. The guy walked on the wrong ship at the wrong time.<br />
Denner: So you snapped his neck, just like that.<br />
Tom: No. It took a few seconds.<br />
Denner: Why are you telling me all this? You do realize what&#8217;s going to happen to you as a result of your confession today?<br />

<p>Judge Denner: You know, before today, I would have said I had seen everything. Now I know I haven&#8217;t seen a damn thing. Even if what you&#8217;re saying is true, Elizabeth Keen still has a lot to answer for.<br />

Keen in the pens until further notice.<br />

<p>Dr. Levin: It appears as if the treatment you were receiving in the clinical trial has slowed the growth of the glioblastoma.<br />

My guess is that&#8217;s what caused the seizure.<br />

<p>Court officer: All rise.<br />
Judge Denner: Oh, sit down. The government has shown nothing but disrespect for this court&#8217;s authority, so spare me the hollow reverence. Let me be clear. Government secrecy ‚Äì the idea that the federal government can act, can surveil, can detail, can interrogate, and even kill American citizens with no oversight or accountability, with no obligation to present the people with the evidence that led to their actions ‚Äì that, in my view, is the gravest threat to our national security. It erodes the very foundation of our great democracy.<br />
[ Connolly enters ]<br />
Denner: This is a system of checks and balances founded on a separation of powers. The fact that any federal prosecutor who utters the magic words, who invokes national security, can suppress cases, can quash subpoenas, can avoid grand juries‚Ä¶  That offends me!<br />
And so I&#8217;m very glad that in this matter, the government has done the responsible thing and complied with my request to review the evidence supporting its claim. Having done so I am satisfied that if Assistant Director Cooper or Agent Keen were compelled to testify, it would expose national secrets and have the potential to do material damage to the national interest.<br />
Prosecutor: Your Honor!<br />
Denner: Let me save you the trouble, Mr. Markin. You and I, for all of our accomplishments, remain rather small fish in this deep and dark federal pool. If that point hasn&#8217;t already been made clear to your boss, I&#8217;m sure it will be very shortly.<br />
Wilcox: You can&#8217;t do this!! A man is dead, a lieutenant in the Metro PD!<br />
Denner: And his death is a tragedy, sir. Agent Keen, his name was Lieutenant Eugene Ames. Never forget it. And let the good work you do from this day forward in some way be a tribute to his memory.<br />
Wilcox [ to Liz ]: That&#8217;s it. You have to live with that. You know what you did.<br />
Prosecutor: Marty, let&#8217;s go.<br />
Wilcox: So, so, t-that&#8217;s how it is now, right? T-the feds are just above the law. [ To Liz ] You know, he was a good man. And now I have to go out in that hallway, and I&#8217;ve got to explain to his wife and daughter how there&#8217;s no justice for a guy who gave most of his life in service to this city.<br />
Connolly: That&#8217;s enough.<br />
[ Wilcox exits ]<br />

Liz: Maybe it should have ended. Maybe he&#8217;s right.<br />

Liz: My ex-husband, Tom Keen?<br />
Connolly: I never met him. There&#8217;s no Tom Keen in federal custody. [ iow, he&#8217;s free to go ]</p>

<h3> Script 2:17 The Longevity Initiative</h3>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<i><b>Blurb:</b> A billionaire is funding research to lengthen human life, but the doctor in charge is taking the research in a very different direction. Tom is faced with threats to his life and seeks refuge.</i></p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Lloyd: This is the third one this month.<br />
Dr. Powell: I&#8217;m well aware of that.<br />
Lloyd: I wasn&#8217;t brought on for this. I thought we agreed we&#8217;re just supposed to find them.<br />
Powell: Things change, Lloyd.<br />
Lloyd: I need you to be more careful.<br />
Powell: Are you telling me how to do my job?<br />
Lloyd: I&#8217;m warning you. One or two more of these experiments goes south, and someone&#8217;s gonna get wind of what we&#8217;re doing here.<br />
Powell: And you&#8217;re being well compensated to take on that risk, Lloyd, but if you&#8217;re telling me that you&#8217;d rather not continue, we will find somebody else. Is that what you&#8217;d prefer? </p>
<p>[ Police radio chatter ]<br />
Officer: License and registration, please.<br />
Lloyd: Evening, Officer.<br />
Officer: Evening.<br />
Lloyd: Sure. No problem.<br />
Officer: What are you hauling here?<br />
Lloyd: Produce.<br />
Officer: And, uh, where to?<br />
Lloyd: Sanborn.<br />
Officer: Sanborn, huh? Are you aware that this highway&#8217;s a drug-smuggling route into Ontario?<br />
Lloyd: I wouldn&#8217;t know anything about that.<br />
Officer: Good, then you wouldn&#8217;t mind me taking a look in the back of the vehicle, would you? You want to remove the sheet, please?<br />
[ Lloyd pulls back sheet revealing woman w a craniotomy ]<br />
Officer: What the‚Äì<br />
[ Lloyd hits him; struggle; Loyd gets Officer&#8217;s gun, points it at him ]<br />

[ Lloyd shoots Officer several times, leaps into his police car and takes off ]<br />
[ Siren wailing ] [ Alarm blaring ] [ Blaring stops ] </p>
<p>Charlene: Honey, what&#8217;s wrong? You left your cane.<br />
Cooper: I didn&#8217;t need it. For the first time in I don&#8217;t know how long, Char, I just got up and walked. [ Both chuckle ] Just a few steps. Hurt like hell.<br />

<p>Tom: Hey, don&#8217;t hang up. I&#8217;m in trouble.<br />

Tom: It&#8217;s not about the harbormaster.<br />
Liz: I can&#8217;t.<br />

The Major: If I can, they can. They flagged you leaving Dresden. Your passports are burned.<br />
Throw me the bag! Get in!<br />
Tom: [ To Liz ] All right, look, I got to go, ‚Äì but I&#8217;ll be all right.<br />
The Major: We got to leave!<br />
Tom: I know! Give me a second!<br />
The Major: Now!<br />
Tom: I know what today is. Have fun at Wing Yee&#8217;s tonight.<br />
Liz: Goodbye, Tom.</p>
<p>[ Red enters,  pulls out bottle of wine ]<br />
Liz: What&#8217;s this?<br />
<b>Red:</b> You don&#8217;t remember, do you?<br />

<h3>Script 2:18 Vanessa Cruz</h3>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<i><b>Blurb:</b> A serial killer is framing members of the one percent. Tom and Liz toy with rekindling a relationship. Red attempts to convince members of the Cabal (formerly known as the alliance) to undergo a restructuring.</i></p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Grunts ]<br />
Salinger: What the hell?<br />
Vanessa Cruz: Just something to help you relax.<br />
[ He gasps ]<br />
Cruz: You really don&#8217;t have any idea who I am, do you, Mr. Salinger?<br />
[ Gasping shallowly ]<br />

[ Gasping continues ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Door opens ]<br />

[ Tom leaves ]<br />

Liz: I came home, and Tom was here.<br />
<b>Red:</b> He&#8217;s back in your life.<br />
Liz: He is not in my life.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I understand what it&#8217;s like to be drawn to something that is unhealthy, to a part of yourself that you are afraid of. But I want you to remember what your life really was with him, and imagine all that it could be without him.<br />
Liz: I don&#8217;t have to imagine.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Good. Because I have a case.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Liz: Toshiro Osaka ‚Äì A Japanese entrepreneur indicted in 2009 and knifed to death by an aggrieved business partner. Miles Chapman ‚Äì He was gunned down in Algiers while avoiding extradition for insider trading. Lester Charles Conway ‚Äì His Ponzi scheme was so massive, he&#8217;s now serving up to 30 years.<br />

She doesn&#8217;t just take their money, she takes their reputations, their freedom, sometimes their lives. Her latest mark was Declan Salinger, a flamboyant venture capitalist who specialized in biotech. He was found last night in a hotel bathtub, needle on the floor, dead from an apparent overdose. His personal laptop was taken into evidence. CSI uncovered corporate withdrawals in excess of $27 million.<br />
Cooper: Navabi, go see Salinger&#8217;s wife. Ressler, Keen, the man in prison ‚Äì Talk to him. If he was framed, I want to know how.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />

<p>‚ãô Gun Salesman: Abby Issa.‚ãò</p>

<p>&nbsp;<br />
Samar: It turns out it&#8217;s a fake.<br />
Liz: What is?<br />
Samar: The entire company. Minnetonka Bankers Health &amp; Life was incorporated in 2006. In nine years, the only policy it issued was to Cruz&#8217;s mother.<br />
Samar: It&#8217;s a shelf corporation.<br />
Liz: You mean &#8220;shell&#8221; corporation?<br />
Samar: No. &#8220;Shelf,&#8221; with an &#8220;f.&#8221; Criminals file incorporation papers. They pay all the fees. It&#8217;s totally legitimate. Then then they put them on the shelf for years, sometimes decades. They pay the minimum corporate tax, build up a credit rating, comply with filings to create an established, creditworthy business that can be used to launder all kinds of transactions.<br />
Ressler: Including phony insurance payments.<br />
Aram: Guys? It looks like this isn&#8217;t the only way Vanessa Cruz has used shelf companies. At least six other victims were all accused of funneling money through shelf corporations they say they didn&#8217;t know existed.<br />
Liz: Samar, you said these corps are being sold to criminals. If we could find the person who sold them to Cruz ‚Äì<br />
Ressler: Then we might find Cruz.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ On phone ]<br />

Liz: I know how much it means to you.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I don&#8217;t think you do.<br />
Liz: And you know how much it means to me to know what part I play in all of this. But you told me it&#8217;s a blackmail file, and I&#8217;m a federal agent. I can&#8217;t just hand over information to you that might give you leverage over people who, for all I know, run our government.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Those people launched a missile strike on the factory to kill us in order to keep their secret a secret.<br />
Liz: This is about Tom, isn&#8217;t it?<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ Chuckling ] No. This is simply about me trying to survive. I&#8217;m perfectly happy to put you in touch with someone who deals in shelf corporations, but I need the Fulcrum. Think about it, Lizzy.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Tom: [ Bumps into guy, lifts wallet ] Sorry, man. Sorry.<br />
[ Cellphone rings ] [ Beeps ]<br />

<p>&nbsp;<br />

‚ãò‚ãô<br />

<p>&nbsp;<br />

Jasper: You know I lean towards the Director. Why should I change that position now?<br />
[ Red steps into view ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Because, Mr. Jasper, you strike me as a man who would prefer to pitch rather than catch.<br />
Jasper: What the hell have you done?<br />
Hobbs: Just hear him out. That&#8217;s all I ask.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Roger is quite right. The Director&#8217;s latest stratagem is hubris. It has very little to do with me and everything to do with the consolidation of his power. If he succeeds, you&#8217;ll become nothing more than his trusted servant. He needs to go. He will go. Tomorrow, after the meeting, after you win this vote with everything that your head and your heart tell you are true.<br />
Jasper: You&#8217;re talking about assassination.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yes, Mr. Jasper. &#8220;Ambition&#8217;s debt must be paid.&#8221;<br />
Jasper: Julius Caesar?<br />
<b>Red:</b> One of my favorites ‚Äì The play, not so much the man. The man was a bit full of himself. He did have a brilliant military mind, but he couldn&#8217;t smell a plot to save his life. Intentional pun.<br />
Jasper: And why is that?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Pride. The subtlest and yet most deadly of the seven sins. Like the Director, he couldn&#8217;t be saved.<br />
Jasper: And which part do you play in all this? Cassius?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Oh, no. I&#8217;m the Rubicon.‚ô§ You simply need to determine which side of history you want to end up on. Who are you, Mr. Jasper? A subordinate who remained slavishly obedient to his master, or the presumptive leader of an organization that will be far more powerful than it has ever been? </p>

February 7, 1944, sank 12 warships, and now they&#8217;re just lying at the bottom of the ocean. It&#8217;s a diver&#8217;s paradise.<br />

Ressler: It&#8217;s not about money. It&#8217;s about revenge. Aram, can you put up all the files? Hernando Cruz jumped off that bridge after being accused of insider trading. He purchased 10,000 shares of stock in Rudman Pharmaceuticals one day before it got approval from the FDA to market a new cancer drug. That stock doubled overnight. Toshiro Osaka, our Japanese entrepreneur When Hernando Cruz made the trade, Osaka was the CFO at Rudman Pharmaceuticals. Miles Chapman ‚Äì He was the regulator who approved the drug. And Drew Roberts was Cruz&#8217;s co-worker who oversaw all of the trades.<br />
Cooper: You think they were in on it with the husband?<br />
Ressler: I&#8217;m saying maybe the husband wasn&#8217;t in on it at all. Maybe they set him up.<br />
Samar: It makes sense. Vanessa Cruz is a frame-up artist. Maybe she got the idea from seeing how easy it was for these people to frame her husband.<br />

Ressler: All one-percenters ‚Äì People who personify the same greed that cost her husband his life.<br />
Cooper: Assuming that she&#8217;s going after everyone who was involved in framing her husband, the question is, who&#8217;s left?<br />

So you and all the other useless, greedy pigs instead gorge yourselves, grow fat on the sweat of the other 99%. So ‚Äì Little piggy ‚Äì I will tell you how this is going to work. You and Abby have been having an affair. There&#8217;s a digital paper trail of texts and pictures. Your fingerprints and DNA are in her apartment. You reserved this room. I&#8217;ve arranged it so the police will believe you&#8217;ve been to her apartment, just like I&#8217;ve arranged for them to believe Abby discovered you were embezzling from your firm and was gonna blackmail you ‚Äì unless you pay her to keep quiet. They&#8217;ll confirm she&#8217;d gone to a lawyer, prepared a sexual-harassment lawsuit, which she threatened you with, so you shot her with the gun she bought to protect herself before turning it on yourself. Abby ‚Äì She has such a big heart. She&#8217;s so innocent, so unsuspecting ‚Äì Just like ‚Äì But this is the only way. You have to pay for what you did.<br />

<h3>Script 2:19 Leonard Caul</h3>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<i><b>Blurb:</b> Red has been shot and cannot risk going to an emergency room where his enemies can find him. He tells Liz to find Leonard Caul. Dembe instructs Liz to go to a flat to get the suitcase Red retrieved from the trunk of the Presidential limo.</i></p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Voice-over: Previously on The Blacklist:<br />
<b>Red:</b>  Alan Fitch directed me to that safe. What does he want me to know?<br />
Leonard Caul (formerly known as Mystery Man): It is happening.<br />
<b>Red:</b>  What is? What&#8217;s happening?<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
<b>Red:</b>  Aram, I need your assistance locating the source of a call that was placed to a pay phone. I can&#8217;t stress enough the urgency of this matter.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
<b>Red:</b>  I don&#8217;t think you have any real comprehension of the depth and breadth of your vulnerability. But only the one who possesses the Fulcrum could possibly fathom that.<br />
The Director: I don&#8217;t think you have it. Don&#8217;t think you ever did.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Hobbs: The Fulcrum ‚Äì if you have it, if you can prove you have it, do it now. Your life depends on it.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Liz: I have the Fulcrum. Tell me what it is, and I&#8217;ll tell you where to find it.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
<b>Red:</b>  Yes. I&#8217;m the one who hired Tom Keen to enter your life.<br />
Liz: Here. [ Gives him the Fulcrum ] This is all you wanted.<br />
<b>Red:</b>  Lizzy. Lizzy! [ Gunshot ]<br />
Dembe: Raymond!<br />
Liz: Dembe! </p>
<p>[ Leonard Caul, a surveillance expert, is working in a red-lit room with photographs of Red, Liz and Tom which cover recent events in the series. At the same time he is listening to recordings of such recent events: ]</p>

<h3>Script 2:20 Quon Zhang</h3>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<i><b>Blurb:</b> Liz prevails on Red for information about the photo of the woman with the small girl she found in Red&#8217;s secret flat. Red captures a cabal member to get information on an upcoming attack and a smuggler of dead bodies reveals he&#8217;s just smuggled in one very much alive.</i></p>

[ Two men enter cemetery. One is Chinese with severe burn scars on the back of his head: Quon Zhang ]<br />
Quon Zhang: Plot 332. This is it.<br />
[ Begins digging ] [ Speaking Chinese ]<br />
[ Worker with flashlight comes across Quon Zhang ]<br />
Worker: Hey, what&#8217;s going on here? Lose the shovel. Keep your hands where I can see them.<br />
What are you doing here?<br />
[ The other man approaches worker from behind. Together they disable him ]</p>
<p>[ Conversing in Chinese ]<br />

Broker: What do we have today?<br />
Quon Zhang: Marjorie Lin, 24, unmarried. She was going for her PhD.<br />
Broker: Cause of death?<br />
Quon Zhang: [ Hands him folder ] Heart attack. No history of illness. Or STDS. As requested.<br />
Broker: How much?<br />
Quon Zhang: $37,000.<br />
Broker: I&#8217;ll take it.<br />
[ Broker leaves ]<br />

<p>Liz: I had the photo enhanced. It&#8217;s a rough extrapolation of features since the face was almost entirely blown out. I ran it through every FBI database from facial recognition, mug shots, surveillance feeds ‚Äì<br />

Liz: Where?<br />

<b>Red:</b> Seeing as how you recently paid a visit to my apartment in Bethesda, you know I have a fondness for the old and somewhat decrepit.<br />
Liz: Dembe asked me to go to get the interface for the Fulcrum.<br />

Red; Please, help yourself.<br />
Liz: [ Groans ] Identification documents for Lien Mah. Fake birth certificate. Fake passport. Death certificate. Proof of embalming.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Everything necessary to convince the U.S. State Department that Lien Mah was a Chinese national who died while visiting the United States and to arrange for her body&#8217;s return to her homeland.<br />
Liz: Who would ship a fictitious Chinese corpse to China?<br />
<b>Red:</b> A rather clever smuggler, I imagine.<br />

<p>Samar: So, we obtained a list from State of all the foreign nationals who died on U.S. soil and were repatriated back to their home countries. Of these, seven in particular stood out.<br />

Cooper: You&#8217;re asking me to fabricate and then leak a classified document.<br />

<p>Aram: Lien Mah&#8217;s body was just delivered to Dulles. The casket&#8217;s scheduled to be on Flight 241 to Beijing.<br />

<p>Agent: Our preliminary x-rays didn&#8217;t reveal any explosive material or objects with a density common to C-4 or other incendiary plastics. We won&#8217;t know what we got for sure till we get inside. To be safe, we&#8217;re gonna let the robot crack it.<br />

How you are supposed to go</p>
<p>If you&#8217;d take the time to cut once you measure twice<br />
To find out the best things to know<br />
A dream in rewind like you&#8217;re a man of the mice<br />
To find out the best way to go<br />
Wouldn&#8217;t that be nice if you could cut once you measured twice?<br />
How are you supposed to know how you are supposed to go </i></p>

<h3>Script 2:21 Karakurt</h3>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<i><b>Blurb:</b> A notorious saboteur, Karakurt, is in country to carry out an attack on a high-value target that will then be blamed on Russia. Red refuses to give Liz more information on her mother, so she turns to other sources. </i></p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Andropov: [ Handing out leaflets ] It&#8217;s time to bring NSA surveillance state to an end. FISA courts are a rubber stamp to trample on your Fourth Amendment right to privacy.<br />
[ Student bumps into him, ]<br />

[ Chuckles, clears throat ] [ Indistinct conversations ]<br />

[ Ticking ] [ Distortion ] [ Student walks away, collapses. Echoing thuds ]<br />
