Liz: I&#8217;m gonna find out the truth.<br />
<b>Red:</b> She makes her real money consulting. Costs a fortune. She did, however, let me name a lipstick color ‚Äì &#8220;Fire In The Hole.&#8221;‚ô§</p>
<p>[ Cellphone vibrating ] [ Beep ] Liz: [ Recording ] You&#8217;ve reached Elizabeth Keen. Please leave your message at the tone.<br />
Tom/Jacob: Hi, Liz. This is, uh, Jacob. [ Horn blares ] Jacob Phelps. Look, I know things are complicated. I know you&#8217;re going through a bad breakup. But from what I heard, the guy&#8217;s a total loser. Couldn&#8217;t cook, made crappy pancakes.‚ô§ So I wanted to see if you would join me for dinner tomorrow. Uh, I made a reservation at 7:00 at this great little place on the corner of 32nd and M, and I hope that you will come. Or not. But, uh, either way, I&#8217;ll be there. [ Beep ] </p>
<p>Dr Kimberly: You&#8217;re right. It is a weapon.<br />
Liz: A WMD?<br />
Kimberly: No. A WID‚Äì a weapon of individual destruction. This is a customized virus, synthesized with the sole intent of killing one specific individual.<br />
<b>Red:</b> How is that possible?<br />
Kimberly: He&#8217;s created a supercharged rotavirus. These are very common. By the age of 5, most of us have been infected multiple times. And with each infection, we build up an immunity. Liz: So it&#8217;s harmless to most people.<br />
Kimberly: All people. Precisely. But this rotavirus has been customized, keyed to infect one individual with a unique genetic sequence, and to devastating effect. According to the animal trials logged in these notes, it attacks the central nervous system within minutes of exposure.<br />
Red: One person.<br />
Liz: But who?<br />
Kimberly: I can only tell you what they&#8217;re doing. I&#8217;m sorry, but I can&#8217;t tell you who they&#8217;re doing it to. [ Goodbye smooches ] [ Sighs ]</p>
<p>Liz: So, we know Karakurt is targeting one person and it&#8217;s keyed to his or her DNA.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Think. He bombed the CIA&#8217;s Russian section. That took time, money and no small amount of risk. What happens when the United States is attacked, suffers grievous loss of life? Liz: We go into lock-down. The bombing bumped the NTAS level to red. But why put the mission at risk by triggering a high-level terrorist alert?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Well, that&#8217;s the downside. The upside is exposure, public attention.‚ô§ Remember, the people behind this went to immense trouble and expense. What does that say about their target?<br />
Liz: He&#8217;s high-value. Someone important.‚ô§ [ Gasps ] Oh, my God, that&#8217;s why he did it. The Memorial Service. The victims will be memorialized at a service at Ascension and Saint Agnes Church. Politicians and military personnel, intelligence officers from overseas will all be there to pay their respects. One of them is the target.</p>
<p>Police security: [ Looking at grainy surveillance photo ] So, this is the guy?<br />
Ressler: That&#8217;s the best we can do. He&#8217;s our prime suspect in the Orea bombing, and we have good reason to believe that he&#8217;s not done yet.<br />
Liz: We need your people to be on high alert.<br />
Police: We&#8217;re looking for a bomb?<br />
Liz: No, we&#8217;ll be prepared for that possibility, but our intel says he&#8217;s after a specific target. We just don&#8217;t know who yet.<br />
Security: We&#8217;ll do our best, but with this many people around, I can&#8217;t promise anything. Safest play is to cancel the event.<br />
Ressler: Believe me, we&#8217;re working on it.</p>
<p>Cooper: Just spoke to Reven Wright. Calling off the memorial service is a nonstarter.<br />
Samar: That&#8217;s a mistake. We have hard evidence of a clear threat.<br />
Cooper: Main Justice is aware. But the public&#8217;s rattled by this bombing, and they want a show of strength. If they cancel, it suggests we can&#8217;t protect our own people on our own turf.<br />
Samar: Maybe we can&#8217;t ‚Äì at this point, we still don&#8217;t know exactly what we&#8217;re dealing with.<br />
Aram: I can tell you what I&#8217;m dealing with‚Äì an impossible problem. So if you&#8217;re counting on me cracking this virus, don&#8217;t.<br />
Samar: Well, what do you have?<br />
Aram: We found the formula for the virus in Karakurt&#8217;s apartment. So my plan was to reverse engineer the process. We are trying millions of DNA combinations. If I could figure out the profile it was engineered to destroy‚Äì<br />
Samar: You could run the profile through the DNA database. If you get a match, that&#8217;s Karakurt&#8217;s target.<br />
Aram: Except it won&#8217;t work ‚Äì not in time, at least. I need hours ‚Äì days, maybe ‚Äì and the memorial will be over long before we can ID the target sequence.<br />
Cooper: Whatever his plan, we have to assume Karakurt&#8217;s already infected himself with the contagion and is a live carrier. Civilian and military security assets have been marshalled for the service. However, the assassin in this case is not armed with something that we can flag with a metal detector. The virus is transmitted through touch. It penetrates the skin. Even brushing up against the target is enough to infect and kill him. It is critical that we nail Karakurt before he can get anywhere near that church. Find him, people! Whatever it takes! </p>
<p>Caul: What are you thinking?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Not me, Leonard. The Director. What is he thinking? His objective is to exacerbate tensions with Russia. He chose to send Karakurt, an assassin known to work for the regime so people will assume Russia is responsible.‚ô§<br />
Caul: So‚Äì<br />
<b>Red:</b> So whoever he&#8217;s targeting next will be an enemy of Russia, an outspoken critic. Someone people will believe the Russians would want to silence.‚ô§</p>
<p>[ Indistinct shouting, chanting. Anti-Russian signs ]<br />
Ressler: Hey, Keen! Keen! have been cleared to attend.<br />
Liz: There&#8217;s Defense, Homeland, CIA, the Bureau on this list. It&#8217;s gonna be hard to narrow it down.<br />
Ressler: Yeah, so much for the good old days where you could just look for the glint of a sniper-rifle scope in a nearby window.</p>
<p><b>Red</b> What does it do, this virus, to the body?<br />
The CDC&#8217;s still breaking it down. But they&#8217;re saying it attacks the central nervous system.<br />
A victim would start shaking within seconds of infection. Disorientation, then labored breathing, convulsions.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Incapacitation within moments of contact. It&#8217;s quite a remarkable feat of engineering. In my experience, such accomplishments don&#8217;t happen overnight.<br />
Caul: You&#8217;re saying they tested it first.<br />
<b>Red:</b> A customized virus deadly to such a small fraction of the population ‚Äì What kind of trial and error would prove useful?<br />
[ Telephone rings ]<br />
Aram: This is Aram.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Agent Mojtabai, I need a list of people admitted to an Emergency Room in the last few days displaying symptoms consistent with the virus you&#8217;re tracking.<br />
Aram: Okay, that&#8217;s not gonna be so easy to put together.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Aram, that kind of catastrophic trauma would certainly have gotten someone&#8217;s attention. It&#8217;s on an autopsy chart somewhere.<br />
Aram: Okay, I hear you, but you have to‚Äì Whoa. Whoa. Bethesda General sent tissue samples to the CDC a few days ago. A suspicious death of a college student. The Center&#8217;s just starting an investigation.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I need that student&#8217;s home address, and I need to speak to Agent Navabi.</p>
<p>Samar: Mrs. Jennings, thank you for seeing me. I know this is an extremely difficult time.<br />
Jennings: I got a message from the CDC about the investigation. But I didn&#8217;t think they&#8217;d be sending someone over so quickly.<br />
Samar: Can you tell me about Connor? What you know so far?<br />
Jennings: [ Sighs ] Not much. Connor was a law student. I was told he was walking across campus when he just started shaking, and then convulsing. One of the doctors suggested he may have contracted a rare form of rotavirus?<br />
Samar: No, you&#8217;re right to be thinking this could be something else entirely. ‚Äì Perhaps malicious.<br />
Jennings: Malicious?<br />
Samar: To be honest, Mrs. Jennings, your son may have been intentionally infected.<br />
Jennings: Is this because<br />
Samar: Is this because?<br />
Jennings: If Connor was targeted by someone capable of this kind of attack, it has to be connected to his father.<br />
Samar: His father?<br />
Jennings: When I was a young staffer on the Hill, I had an affair with the man I was working for.<br />
We were stupid, and I got pregnant. Even then, he had his eyes set on a big political future, so I agreed to go away. I made a deal to receive ongoing support from him.</p>
<p>Samar: Senator Hawkins‚Äì he&#8217;s the target. They tested the virus on his son, the closest possible genetic match. You need to find the Senator before Karakurt does.<br />
[ Indistinct shouting ]<br />
Ressler: Hey, Keen! Samar&#8217;s reaching out to Hawkins&#8217; office. He&#8217;s not inside, so we still got a shot of keeping him clear.<br />
Liz: I&#8217;ll check the drive-ups. Any word from Metro?<br />
Ressler: Negative. If Karakurt&#8217;s inside, nobody&#8217;s spotted him yet.</p>
<p>Security: Step up, please. Name?<br />
Karakurt: Flemming, European Wire.<br />
Security: Flemming, press badge 6362. We&#8217;re gonna need to check the case. We&#8217;re good  [ Zipper closes ] He&#8217;s on the Main Justice press list.</p>
<p><b>Red:</b> It&#8217;s time, Harold. Call Tom Connolly. Tell him you need to see him immediately. I&#8217;m assuming at the moment he has no idea you&#8217;ve identified Karakurt&#8217;s intended victim, which is why you need to tell him.<br />
Cooper: Why would I do that?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Because he&#8217;ll be caught off guard. And in addition to enhancing your credibility with him, it&#8217;ll make him doubt whether or not to move forward.<br />
Cooper: You think he&#8217;ll call off the attack?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I think it&#8217;s worth the attempt. What&#8217;s the latest from Agents Keen and Ressler?<br />
Cooper: Still no sign of Karakurt. Agent Navabi&#8217;s on the line now with one of Hawkins&#8217; aides.<br />
Samar: Listen to me. It&#8217;s not a potential threat. The Bureau has confirmed that a direct attack on the Senator is imminent. No, I cannot confirm my source. Then you need to find whoever is with him and deliver the message. It&#8217;s not safe to attend the service. You need to find him.</p>
<p>[ Senator Hawkins is talking to aide in car ]<br />
Aide: You&#8217;ll be third to the podium, Senator. After the minister and the family representative, they&#8217;ll have a moment of silence, and then‚Äì<br />
Hawkins: We&#8217;ll be sitting here forever. This is fine, Patrick. I&#8217;ll walk.</p>
<p>[ Indistinct shouting ]<br />
Senator Hawkins, how are you?<br />
Man: Welcome, sir.<br />
Hawkins: Thank you.<br />
[ Police radio chatter ] [ Camera shutter clicks ] </p>
<p>Connolly: Harold, your cooperation was instrumental in Karakurt&#8217;s escape. Everything&#8217;s on track, thanks to you.<br />
Cooper: Don&#8217;t thank me yet.<br />
Connolly: Why? Is there a problem?<br />
Cooper: My people are closing in on him now. They know the Orea bombing was just the first in a series of attacks. They know about the virus.<br />
Connolly: I see. Well, thank you for letting me know. But why are you letting me know? And don&#8217;t tell me you want to help because I know you&#8217;d like nothing better than to strangle me right now.<br />
Cooper: You&#8217;re right. I&#8217;m letting you know because I want you to call it off. I can&#8217;t control Reddington, and I can&#8217;t misdirect my people again without drawing suspicion. It&#8217;s only a matter of time until they stop Karakurt.<br />
Connolly: Stop him from what? They don&#8217;t even know his target.<br />
Cooper: Clifford Hawkins. Call it off, Tom. If the Director really wants him dead, he can find another way on another day.<br />
Connolly: No. Today is the day. I appreciate your concern, but everything should be fine. Strange days, don&#8217;t you think? Assassins don&#8217;t need knives or guns or bombs. All you have to do is answer a few questions and shake the wrong man&#8217;s hand.‚ô§</p>
<p>[ Cellphone rings ]<br />
Cooper: The press corps. Get over there now. I think Karakurt may be posing as a reporter.<br />
Woman: Hey, he&#8217;s just pulling into the service now.<br />
Karakurt: [ Reaches out hand ] Senator Hawkins.<br />
[ Liz tackles him ]<br />
Liz: Get him away! Get him away from us! Come with us, sir!<br />
[ Engine turns over ] [ Tires squeal ]<br />

The man responsible for the Orea bombing‚Äì Karakurt?<br />
Hawkins: I was briefed. Was that him?<br />
Liz: We&#8217;ll explain everything, sir. Right now, we need to get you to a secure location.<br />
Hawkins: Thank you. Please, call my wife, tell her I&#8217;m okay?<br />
Liz: Sir?<br />
[ Choking ]<br />
Liz: Sir! We need to get him to a hospital now! He&#8217;s been infected! Sir! </p>
<p>Samar: Bethesda says Hawkins is critical. They&#8217;ve called in the hospital chaplain.<br />
Cooper: He didn&#8217;t touch Karakurt?<br />
Ressler: No, sir.<br />
Cooper: Then what the hell happened?<br />

<p>Liz: Karakurt. That means &#8220;Spider,&#8221; right?‚ô§<br />
Karakurt: Kara-what? Huh? Look, I don&#8217;t know what that is. My name is Jonas Flemming. I&#8217;m a reporter for the European Wire. I live in Rotterdam.<br />

Liz: We have a recording of you and Andropov. We know he engineered a drug designed to kill the Senator. We know you&#8217;re infected.<br />
Karakurt: No, no, no, no. My credentials were taken from me when I arrived, but they were vetted by your Department Of Justice. Please, call.<br />
Liz: You didn&#8217;t touch the Senator. How was the virus delivered?<br />
Ressler: You can rig your little story, but you can&#8217;t rig your blood. We&#8217;re running it right now. And when it comes back positive for that virus that killed Hawkins, we got you.</p>
<p><b>Red:</b> Hello, Anton. Relax. If I had bad intentions for this visit, you&#8217;d know by now.<br />
Velov: [ Russian accent ] You&#8217;re Raymond Reddington.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I am. And if I&#8217;m right, you&#8217;re the same Anton Velov who once led a Spetsnaz Special Forces Unit called The Zarubin Group.<br />
Velov:  I&#8217;m surprised we never met. For many years, while you were still with US Counterintelligence, I considered you the KGB&#8217;s greatest enemy.‚ô§<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ Laughing ] Oh, my God. That feels like ages ago. For what it&#8217;s worth, I was young. I had no concept of what a real enemy looked like. [ Inhales deeply ] But I do now.‚ô§ Which is why I&#8217;m hoping you and I might prove to be fast friends.<br />
Velov: What can I do?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I know you&#8217;re working with the CIA as an informant for the Office of Russian and European Analysis. Since those agents are tragically no longer with us, I was thinking perhaps you might become an asset for me.<br />
Velov: The American government. They may not be done with me yet. I got a phone call from FBI. An agent named Elizabeth Keen.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Really? What about?<br />
Velov: She wants to meet. She was asking about Katarina Rostova.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Did you know Katarina Rostova?<br />
Velov: No, not personally. All I know are the same old ghost stories we all share.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Well, if you were in my employ, I would have to insist you not speak to anyone from the FBI or any other US intelligence agency.<br />
Velov: Of course. And Agent Keen, she wasn&#8217;t the first. Sometime back, two men from Justice Department come and ask me about Katarina. I suppose they think I am one of the few people left who still remember the old stories.<br />
<b>Red:</b> What sort of stories?<br />
Velov:They were asking about her KGB contacts, where she lived, and about a child.‚ô§<br />
<b>Red:</b> They asked about a child?<br />
Velov: Yes, many times.&#8221;Tell me about her child.&#8221; I said, &#8220;All I know is they say she had a daughter.&#8221;‚ô§<br />
<b>Red:</b> Dembe, the phone.</p>
<p>Karakurt: How many times are we gonna go through this? That picture isn&#8217;t me. Call my office.<br />
Check my visa, check my identity.<br />
Ressler: We know you&#8217;re working for the Cabal. We know what they&#8217;re capable of.<br />
Liz: Was this the plan all along, to protect you with this identity?  The Cabal has people in the government all over the world. It wouldn&#8217;t be hard for them to create a Jonas Flemming, give him a history.<br />
Aram: The Crime Lab just called. They&#8217;re saying his blood tested negative for the virus.<br />
Ressler: Negative? That&#8217;s not possible.‚ô§</p>
<p>[ Cellphone vibrates ]<br />
Liz: Hey, I got to call you right back.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Lizzy, you need to get out of there now.‚ô§<br />
Liz: Why? Where are you? What&#8217;s going on?<br />
<b>Red:</b> You&#8217;ve been set up. The Cabal&#8217;s been asking about you, Lizzy. They know who your mother was. You&#8217;ve been set up. You were there when the Orea building was bombed. They wanted you to save Clifford Hawkins. They sent Karakurt to the memorial to make you think he was the threat so you would secure the Senator and infect him in the process.<br />
Liz: I don&#8217;t have the virus.‚ô§<br />
<b>Red:</b> You do, Lizzy. I don&#8217;t need a test to know that you do.‚ô§ Your mother was a Russian spy, and now they&#8217;ve made it look like you are, too. You have the virus. You infected the Senator, and now they will come for you. You need to get out of there now.‚ô§</p>
<p>[ Elevator opens. Connolly walks out with two armed guards. Liz eludes them ]</p>

<h3 id="connolly">üî¥ 2:22 Tom Connolly</h3>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
 <b>üî¥ Script: 2:22 Tom Connolly  </b></p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Last updated: 8/8/2015<br />
Program air date: 5/14/2015 in the US<br />
Script with extras: <a href="http://wp.me/pDKwi-Wi" rel="nofollow">http://wp.me/pDKwi-Wi</a><br />
Source: Raw scripts from Springfield [UK]: <a href="http://bit.ly/1Do56Zu" rel="nofollow">http://bit.ly/1Do56Zu</a> (captions)<br />

<p>&nbsp;<br />
<b>Created by:</b> Jon <b>Bokenkamp</b><br />
<b>Director:</b> Michael <b>Watkins</b><br />

<p>&nbsp;<br />
<i><b>Blurb:</b> Liz is being framed for the murder of a U.S. Senator as The Cabal tries to stir up trouble with Russia. Red does what he has threatened for 20 years and Cooper gets a new prognosis. The Season 2 Finale. </i></p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Previously on The Blacklist:<br />
Navabi: The owner is Anton Velov. My belief is he&#8217;s the CI.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />

After being infected by what authorities describe as a biological agent. Or the act of a re element within Russia. <p>Liz: I&#8217;m being framed.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yes, and by the end of the day, they&#8217;ll identify you by name.<br />
Liz: Anyone could have infected Hawkins. He must have shaken dozens of hands at that memorial.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Within hours, they will all have tested negative for the virus.<br />
Liz: You can&#8217;t know that. This is insane.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Lizzy, you walked into the Director&#8217;s office and played him the Fulcrum. You are the enemy. They&#8217;re crawling over every place you&#8217;ve ever lived and worked, every file and hard drive like fire ants on a grasshopper.<br />
Liz: They won&#8217;t find anything.<br />
<b>Red:</b> That&#8217;ll suit their purposes just fine. Anything they do find, they&#8217;ll erase so they can say you destroyed evidence to hide your involvement in the plot. And when they eventually restore what few pieces they do want to be found, they will not be kind to you. You need to get out.<br />
Liz: If I run, it&#8217;ll only make me look guilty. I&#8217;ll be playing right into their hands.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You&#8217;re already in their hands. The only thing they haven&#8217;t done is closed their fist. Go. Now. I&#8217;ll be there in three minutes.<br />
Liz: No. They can&#8217;t prove I did anything wrong. They can call me a criminal, but I&#8217;m not gonna act like one.</p>
<p>[ Beep ]<br />
Connolly: Where is Elizabeth Keen? Harold, a warrant has been issued for her arrest. Anyone hiding her will be charged with aiding and abetting a terrorist, including you.<br />
Cooper: You used me. You wanted me to know Karakurt was posing as a reporter. You wanted me to tell Keen where to intercept Hawkins. I don&#8217;t know how this helps you, framing an FBI agent. Nobody will believe she&#8217;s an assassin.<br />
Connolly: She was at Orea when it blew up.<br />
Cooper: So were dozens of others.<br />
Connolly: Yes, but I&#8217;ll bet that only her prints are found on the truck bomb. She&#8217;ll also test positive for the virus that killed Senator Hawkins.<br />
Cooper: He&#8217;s not dead.<br />
Connolly: Yet.<br />
Cooper: You won&#8217;t get away with it. Keen is a distinguished agent.<br />
Connolly: Yes, and the daughter of a Russian KGB asset. She failed to mention that, did she? Agent Keen&#8217;s been hiding secrets from you&#8211; secrets that clearly implicate her as an enemy of this country. She was handpicked by a notorious fugitive to assist in expanding his criminal empire. The two of them have been using this task force to do Reddington&#8217;s bidding. And before you tell me that&#8217;s crazy, can you really tell me that isn&#8217;t true? I will never help you do this. I don&#8217;t need your help, Harold. A simple blood test from Agent Keen will be as compelling as a signed confession.<br />
[ Liz has been listening ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
News: The entire area around St. Agnes has been quarantined, and individuals who might have been exposed, as well, have been detained inside the church.
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ Door opens ]<br />
Senator: You have no legal authority to hold us here.<br />
Ressler: Senator, I understand you&#8217;re upset, but we need everyone&#8217;s full cooperation. People are saying Hawkins was infected with some sort of virus.<br />
Senator: You think we&#8217;re infected?<br />
Ressler: Probably not, but that&#8217;s why we set up a mobile lab.<br />
Senator: You don&#8217;t have probable cause to hold us. You really want a US senator claiming wrongful arrest and imprisonment?<br />
Ressler: Hey, someone just tried to assassinate a colleague of yours. Nobody&#8217;s going anywhere. But when we&#8217;re done here, if you want to file a complaint or a lawsuit, be my guest. Until then, get back in the line.</p>
<p>Ressler: What have you found on the feeds?<br />
Samar: We&#8217;ve been looking at surveillance feeds from the moment he arrived until the moment he collapsed. We&#8217;ve rounded up everyone he came into contact with.<br />
Ressler: Which means the killer&#8217;s in this room.</p>
<p>Connolly: I&#8217;ve assigned Reven Wright to oversee the investigation of Agent Keen. I&#8217;m confident she&#8217;ll follow the facts.<br />
Cooper: Those facts are not proven.<br />
Connolly: If you don&#8217;t want to help us, that&#8217;s fine, but I&#8217;m sure I don&#8217;t need to remind you what will happen if you actively stand in our way. You&#8217;ll be charged with perjury in the Harbormaster case and leaking privileged grand-jury proceedings. And then there&#8217;s Charlene.<br />
Cooper: You need to leave now.<br />
Connolly: As for the clinical trial, I can&#8217;t imagine that will continue.<br />
Cooper: Did you hear what I said? You can take your pills and your clinical trial. [ Throws pills on floor ] I would rather die than be part of this.<br />
Connolly: Escort Director Cooper to his car. I&#8217;m placing him on administrative leave until we&#8217;re finished here. And find Elizabeth Keen.</p>
<p>Ressler: There must be some mistake.<br />

Cooper: Keen ‚Äì Run.</p>
<p>[ Screams ] [ Horn blares ] [ Cellphone ringing ]<br />
Liz: Excuse me.<br />
[ Beep ]<br />
Liz: [ On phone ] Ressler?<br />
Ressler: Where the hell are you? Listen to me.<br />
Liz: Harold Cooper ‚Äì he had nothing to do with this.<br />
Ressler: You need to turn yourself in.<br />
Liz: Did you hear me? He&#8217;s innocent.<br />
Ressler: You are a wanted fugitive. You murdered the Attorney General of the United States. You have to come in.<br />
Liz: I can&#8217;t.<br />
Ressler: Damn it, Liz, wake up. You keep running, you will be hunted down.<br />
Liz: I know.<br />
Ressler: By me. Don&#8217;t make me do this. Please, Liz, tell me where you are. [ Beep ] Tell me, and I can get ‚Äì [ Beeping ]<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Dialing ] [ Cellphone rings ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ On phone ] Lizzy.<br />
Liz: I need your help.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Where are you?<br />
Liz: I killed Tom Connolly.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I know. Where are you?<br />
Liz: I&#8217;m on, uh, 7th and L, Northeast.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m gonna call you back in two minutes with an address. I need you to get there. I&#8217;m gonna get you out.<br />
[ Beep ] [ Dialing ] [ Ringing ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ On phone ] It&#8217;s me. I need to travel.</p>
<p>Liz: I remember.<br />
[ Car door closes ] [ Engine turns over ]<br />
Liz: I remember everything.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Remember what?<br />
Liz: The night of the fire. I know what happened, and I understand why you didn&#8217;t want me to find out. When I pulled the trigger ‚Äì When I shot Connolly, I It came back to me. It was like I was there. I could hear them arguing. [ Flashback. Distorted shouting ] He was hurting her. And I know why my father died that night.‚ô§<br />
Woman: [ Distorted ] Masha?<br />

<b>Red:</b> Yeah.</p>
<p><i>[ ‚ô´ Elton John&#8217;s Rocket Man plays.</i> Ressler pins up Liz&#8217;s on the display board. A man pins up a &#8220;Ten Most Wanted Poster&#8221; of Elizabeth Keen next to that of Raymond &#8220;Red&#8221; Reddington ]</p>

<p>Liz: You&#8217;re my sin eater.‚ô§<br />

<script type="text/javascript">
var highlander_expando_javascript = function(){
	var input = document.createElement( 'input' ),
	    comment = jQuery( '#comment' );

	if ( 'placeholder' in input ) {
		comment.attr( 'placeholder', jQuery( '.comment-textarea label' ).remove().text() );
	}

	// Expando Mode: start small, then auto-resize on first click + text length
	jQuery( '#comment-form-identity' ).hide();
	jQuery( '#comment-form-subscribe' ).hide();
	jQuery( '#commentform .form-submit' ).hide();

	comment.css( { 'height':'10px' } ).one( 'focus', function() {
		var timer = setInterval( HighlanderComments.resizeCallback, 10 )
		jQuery( this ).animate( { 'height': HighlanderComments.initialHeight } ).delay( 100 ).queue( function(n) { clearInterval( timer ); HighlanderComments.resizeCallback(); n(); } );
		jQuery( '#comment-form-identity' ).slideDown();
		jQuery( '#comment-form-subscribe' ).slideDown();
		jQuery( '#commentform .form-submit' ).slideDown();
	});
}
jQuery(document).ready( highlander_expando_javascript );
</script>

<script id='wpgroho-js-extra'>
var WPGroHo = {"my_hash":""};
</script>
<script type='text/javascript' src='https://s0.wp.com/wp-content/mu-plugins/gravatar-hovercards/wpgroho.js?m=1380573781h'></script>

	<script>
		//initialize and attach hovercards to all gravatars
		jQuery( document ).ready( function( $ ) {

			if (typeof Gravatar === "undefined"){
				return;
			}

			if ( typeof Gravatar.init !== "function" ) {
				return;
			}			

			Gravatar.profile_cb = function( hash, id ) {
				WPGroHo.syncProfileData( hash, id );
			};
			Gravatar.my_hash = WPGroHo.my_hash;
			Gravatar.init( 'body', '#wp-admin-bar-my-account' );
		});
